<h5>5.1.1 Vector Equation of a Line</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Find the vector equation of the line passing through $A(1, -2, 3)$ with direction vector $\vec{d} = (2, 1, -1)$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>The vector equation of a line is completely determined by a point $P_0$ on the line and a direction vector $\vec{d} \neq \vec{0}$.</p>
<p>The general form is:
$$\vec{r} = \vec{OP_0} + \lambda\,\vec{d}, \quad \lambda \in \mathbb{R}$$</p>
<p>In our case, $\vec{OP_0} = (1, -2, 3)$ and $\vec{d} = (2, 1, -1)$, so:
$$(x, y, z) = (1, -2, 3) + \lambda(2, 1, -1)$$</p>
<p>That is:
$$\boxed{(x, y, z) = (1 + 2\lambda,\; -2 + \lambda,\; 3 - \lambda), \quad \lambda \in \mathbb{R}}$$</p>
<p><strong>Verification:</strong> For $\lambda = 0$ we obtain the point $A(1,-2,3)$ ✓. The direction of the vector $(2,1,-1)$ is the same as $\vec{d}$ ✓.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Write the vector equation of the line passing through $P(0, 1, 2)$ with direction vector $\vec{d} = (3, 0, -2)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The vector equation is:
$$(x, y, z) = (0, 1, 2) + \lambda(3, 0, -2), \quad \lambda \in \mathbb{R}$$
That is, $(x,y,z) = (3\lambda,\; 1,\; 2-2\lambda)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find the vector equation of the line passing through the points $A(2, -1, 0)$ and $B(4, 3, -2)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The direction vector is $\vec{AB} = B - A = (4-2,\; 3-(-1),\; -2-0) = (2, 4, -2)$.
We can simplify by dividing by 2: $\vec{d} = (1, 2, -1)$.
Taking $A$ as the base point:
$$(x, y, z) = (2, -1, 0) + \lambda(1, 2, -1), \quad \lambda \in \mathbb{R}$$
<strong>Check:</strong> For $\lambda = 2$: $(2+2, -1+4, 0-2) = (4,3,-2) = B$ ✓</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the vector equation of the line $r$ passing through $A(1, 2, -1)$ that is parallel to the line $s: (x,y,z) = (3,0,1) + \mu(2,-1,4)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Two lines are parallel if and only if their direction vectors are proportional. The direction vector of $s$ is $\vec{d}_s = (2,-1,4)$, which also serves as the direction vector of $r$.
The vector equation of $r$ is:
$$(x, y, z) = (1, 2, -1) + \lambda(2, -1, 4), \quad \lambda \in \mathbb{R}$$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The line $r$ has vector equation $(x,y,z) = (1,0,-3) + \lambda(-2,1,2)$. Determine whether the point $Q(5, -2, -7)$ belongs to $r$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> We substitute the coordinates of $Q$ into the vector equation and check whether a unique value of $\lambda$ exists:
$$5 = 1 - 2\lambda \Rightarrow \lambda = -2$$
$$-2 = 0 + \lambda \Rightarrow \lambda = -2$$
$$-7 = -3 + 2\lambda \Rightarrow 2\lambda = -4 \Rightarrow \lambda = -2$$
All three values are equal, $\lambda = -2$ in all three cases, therefore $Q \in r$ ✓.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Let $r$ be the line passing through $A(2,1,-3)$ and $B(4,-1,1)$, and $s$ the line passing through $C(1,3,0)$ with direction vector $\vec{d}_s = (1,-1,2)$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Write the vector equation of $r$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Determine whether $r$ and $s$ are the same line, parallel, intersecting, or skew.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $\vec{AB} = (4-2, -1-1, 1-(-3)) = (2,-2,4)$. Simplifying: $\vec{d}_r = (1,-1,2)$.
$$r:\; (x,y,z) = (2,1,-3) + \lambda(1,-1,2)$$</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> The direction vectors are $\vec{d}_r = (1,-1,2)$ and $\vec{d}_s = (1,-1,2)$: they are proportional (equal), so $r \parallel s$ or $r = s$.
We check whether $C(1,3,0) \in r$:
$$1 = 2 + \lambda \Rightarrow \lambda = -1$$
$$3 = 1 - \lambda = 1-(-1) = 2 \neq 3$$
The second equation is not satisfied, so $C \notin r$.
<strong>Conclusion:</strong> $r$ and $s$ are <strong>parallel</strong> (non-coincident).</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The vector equation of the line passing through $P(1,2,3)$ with direction vector $\vec{d}=(0,1,0)$ is:</li>
<li>a) $(x,y,z) = (1,2,3) + \lambda(1,2,3)$</li>
<li>b) $(x,y,z) = (0,1,0) + \lambda(1,2,3)$</li>
<li>c) $(x,y,z) = (1,2,3) + \lambda(0,1,0)$</li>
<li>d) $(x,y,z) = (1,2,3) + \lambda(1,0,0)$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) The form is $\vec{r} = \vec{OP_0} + \lambda\vec{d}$, with point $P(1,2,3)$ and $\vec{d}=(0,1,0)$. This line is parallel to the $OY$ axis.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>How many distinct direction vectors can a line in space have?</li>
<li>a) Exactly one</li>
<li>b) Exactly two (one for each direction)</li>
<li>c) Infinitely many, all proportional to each other</li>
<li>d) Infinitely many, with no restriction</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) The direction vector of a line is not unique: any non-zero scalar multiple of a direction vector is also a direction vector of the same line. All such vectors are proportional to each other.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.1.2 Parametric Equations of a Line</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Obtain the parametric equations of the line passing through $A(-1, 3, 2)$ with direction vector $\vec{d} = (4, -2, 1)$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>We start from the vector equation: $(x,y,z) = (-1,3,2) + \lambda(4,-2,1)$.</p>
<p>Equating coordinate by coordinate gives the <strong>parametric equations</strong>:</p>
<p>$$\boxed{\begin{cases} x = -1 + 4\lambda \ y = 3 - 2\lambda \ z = 2 + \lambda \end{cases}, \quad \lambda \in \mathbb{R}}$$</p>
<p>Each value of $\lambda \in \mathbb{R}$ determines a unique point on the line.</p>
<p><strong>Example of use:</strong> For $\lambda = 1$: $(x,y,z) = (3, 1, 3)$, which is another point on the line.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Write the parametric equations of the line passing through $P(2,0,-1)$ with direction vector $\vec{d}=(1,3,-2)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong>
$$\begin{cases} x = 2 + \lambda \ y = 3\lambda \ z = -1 - 2\lambda \end{cases}, \quad \lambda \in \mathbb{R}$$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find the parametric equations of the line passing through $A(0,0,0)$ and $B(1,-2,3)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The direction vector is $\vec{AB} = (1,-2,3)$. Taking $A$ as the base point:
$$\begin{cases} x = \lambda \ y = -2\lambda \ z = 3\lambda \end{cases}, \quad \lambda \in \mathbb{R}$$
This line passes through the origin with direction $(1,-2,3)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>From the parametric equations $\begin{cases} x = 2 + 3\lambda \ y = -1 + \lambda \ z = 4 - 2\lambda \end{cases}$, find the intersection point of the line with the plane $z = 0$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The plane $z=0$ corresponds to $z=0$ in the parametric equations:
$$4 - 2\lambda = 0 \Rightarrow \lambda = 2$$
Substituting $\lambda = 2$:
$$x = 2 + 6 = 8, \quad y = -1 + 2 = 1, \quad z = 0$$
The intersection point with the plane $z=0$ is $\mathbf{(8, 1, 0)}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>A line has parametric equations $x = 1+t$, $y = 2-t$, $z = -1+2t$. Find the points on the line whose $x$-coordinate equals its $y$-coordinate.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> We impose $x = y$:
$$1 + t = 2 - t \Rightarrow 2t = 1 \Rightarrow t = \frac{1}{2}$$
Substituting $t = 1/2$:
$$x = 1 + \frac{1}{2} = \frac{3}{2}, \quad y = 2 - \frac{1}{2} = \frac{3}{2}, \quad z = -1 + 1 = 0$$
The desired point is $\left(\dfrac{3}{2}, \dfrac{3}{2}, 0\right)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Consider the lines:
   $$r:\; \begin{cases} x = 1 + 2t \ y = -t \ z = 3 + t \end{cases} \qquad s:\; \begin{cases} x = 3 + \mu \ y = 2 + \mu \ z = 5 - \mu \end{cases}$$</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Find the direction vectors of $r$ and $s$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Determine whether $r$ and $s$ intersect. If they do, find the intersection point.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> From the parametric equations: $\vec{d}_r = (2,-1,1)$ and $\vec{d}_s = (1,1,-1)$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> For the lines to intersect, the system $r = s$ must have a solution:
$$1+2t = 3+\mu \;\Rightarrow\; 2t - \mu = 2 \quad (I)$$
$$-t = 2+\mu \;\Rightarrow\; -t - \mu = 2 \quad (II)$$
$$3+t = 5-\mu \;\Rightarrow\; t + \mu = 2 \quad (III)$$</p>
<p>From $(II)$ and $(III)$: adding, $-t - \mu + t + \mu = 4 \Rightarrow 0 = 4$, <strong>contradiction</strong>.
The system is inconsistent. The direction vectors are not proportional (the lines are not parallel), and they do not intersect, therefore $r$ and $s$ are <strong>skew lines</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The parametric equations $x = 2 - t,\; y = 1,\; z = 3 + 2t$ correspond to a line that:</li>
<li>a) Is parallel to the $OX$ axis</li>
<li>b) Is parallel to the $OY$ axis</li>
<li>c) Is parallel to the $XOY$ plane</li>
<li>d) Passes through the origin of coordinates</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) The direction vector is $(-1, 0, 2)$. Since the $y$-component is constant ($y=1$), the line is parallel to the $XOZ$ plane and, in particular, parallel to the $XOY$ plane. (It has no $y$-component, which implies it is parallel to the $XOZ$ plane, not the $XOY$ plane.) Correction: the direction vector $(-1,0,2)$ has $y$-component $0$, so the line is <strong>parallel to the $XOZ$ plane</strong>. The correct answer among those given is c), since it also does not pass through the origin ($y$ would be 0, not 1).</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The line $r$ has parametric equations $x=3,\; y=1+2\lambda,\; z=-2+\lambda$. What is its direction vector?</li>
<li>a) $(3, 1, -2)$</li>
<li>b) $(0, 2, 1)$</li>
<li>c) $(1, 2, 1)$</li>
<li>d) $(3, 2, 1)$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) In the parametric equations $x = 3 + 0\cdot\lambda$, $y = 1+2\lambda$, $z = -2+\lambda$, the coefficients of $\lambda$ are $(0, 2, 1)$, which is the direction vector.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.1.3 Symmetric (or Continuous) Equations of a Line</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Obtain the symmetric (continuous) equations of the line passing through $A(3, -1, 2)$ with direction vector $\vec{d} = (2, 4, -3)$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>The parametric equations are:
$$x = 3 + 2\lambda, \quad y = -1 + 4\lambda, \quad z = 2 - 3\lambda$$</p>
<p>Solving for $\lambda$ from each:
$$\lambda = \frac{x-3}{2}, \quad \lambda = \frac{y+1}{4}, \quad \lambda = \frac{z-2}{-3}$$</p>
<p>Equating all three expressions (since all equal $\lambda$):</p>
<p>$$\boxed{\frac{x-3}{2} = \frac{y+1}{4} = \frac{z-2}{-3}}$$</p>
<p>These are the <strong>symmetric</strong> (or continuous) equations of the line. The denominator of each fraction is the corresponding component of the direction vector.</p>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> If a component of the direction vector is zero, that coordinate is constant and is written separately. For example, if $d_y = 0$, we write $y = y_0$ and $\dfrac{x-x_0}{d_x} = \dfrac{z-z_0}{d_z}$.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Write the symmetric equations of the line with parametric equations $x = 1+2t,\; y = -3+t,\; z = 5-4t$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> We solve for $t$ from each equation:
$$t = \frac{x-1}{2}, \quad t = y+3, \quad t = \frac{z-5}{-4}$$
The symmetric equations are:
$$\frac{x-1}{2} = \frac{y+3}{1} = \frac{z-5}{-4}$$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find the symmetric equations of the line passing through $A(2,1,-3)$ and $B(5,1,0)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{AB} = (3, 0, 3)$. Since the $y$-component is zero, the $y$-coordinate remains constant:
$$y = 1 \quad \text{and} \quad \frac{x-2}{3} = \frac{z+3}{3}$$
Simplifying the second: $x - 2 = z + 3$, i.e. $x - z = 5$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The line $r$ has symmetric equations $\dfrac{x+1}{3} = \dfrac{y-2}{-1} = \dfrac{z}{2}$. Find a point on $r$ and its direction vector. Determine the parametric equations.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong>
- <strong>Point:</strong> setting each fraction equal to $0$: $x+1=0, y-2=0, z=0$, so $P(-1, 2, 0) \in r$.
- <strong>Direction vector:</strong> the denominators give $\vec{d} = (3,-1,2)$.
- <strong>Parametric equations:</strong>
$$x = -1+3\lambda, \quad y = 2-\lambda, \quad z = 2\lambda, \quad \lambda \in \mathbb{R}$$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Check whether the point $Q(5, 0, 4)$ belongs to the line $\dfrac{x-1}{2} = \dfrac{y+1}{-\frac{1}{2}} = \dfrac{z-2}{1}$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> We substitute $Q(5,0,4)$:
$$\frac{5-1}{2} = \frac{4}{2} = 2, \quad \frac{0+1}{-\frac{1}{2}} = \frac{1}{-0{,}5} = -2, \quad \frac{4-2}{1} = 2$$
The first and third quotients equal $2$, but the second equals $-2$. <strong>The three quotients are not equal</strong>, therefore $Q \notin r$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Let the line $r:\;\dfrac{x-2}{1} = \dfrac{y+1}{2} = \dfrac{z-3}{-2}$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Write the parametric equations of $r$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Find the intersection point of $r$ with the plane $\pi:\; 2x - y + z = 1$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Calculate the distance from the point $A(2,-1,3)$ to the plane $\pi$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Direction vector $\vec{d} = (1,2,-2)$, point $P(2,-1,3)$:
$$r:\;\begin{cases} x = 2 + \lambda \ y = -1 + 2\lambda \ z = 3 - 2\lambda \end{cases}$$</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Substituting into $\pi$:
$$2(2+\lambda) - (-1+2\lambda) + (3-2\lambda) = 1$$
$$4 + 2\lambda + 1 - 2\lambda + 3 - 2\lambda = 1$$
$$8 - 2\lambda = 1 \Rightarrow \lambda = \frac{7}{2}$$
Intersection point:
$$x = 2 + \frac{7}{2} = \frac{11}{2}, \quad y = -1 + 7 = 6, \quad z = 3 - 7 = -4$$
<strong>Intersection:</strong> $\left(\dfrac{11}{2}, 6, -4\right)$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> The point $A(2,-1,3)$ is precisely the base point of $r$, which lies on $r$. We check whether $A \in \pi$:
$$2(2)-(-1)+3 = 4+1+3 = 8 \neq 1$$
$A \notin \pi$. Distance:
$$d(A,\pi) = \frac{|2\cdot2 - (-1) + 3 - 1|}{\sqrt{4+1+1}} = \frac{|4+1+3-1|}{\sqrt{6}} = \frac{7}{\sqrt{6}} = \frac{7\sqrt{6}}{6}$$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Which of the following is the symmetric form of the line with parametric equations $x=2+3t,\; y=1-t,\; z=-4+2t$?</li>
<li>a) $\dfrac{x+2}{3} = \dfrac{y-1}{-1} = \dfrac{z-4}{2}$</li>
<li>b) $\dfrac{x-2}{3} = \dfrac{y-1}{-1} = \dfrac{z+4}{2}$</li>
<li>c) $\dfrac{x-2}{3} = \dfrac{y+1}{-1} = \dfrac{z+4}{2}$</li>
<li>d) $\dfrac{x-3}{2} = \dfrac{y+1}{1} = \dfrac{z-2}{-4}$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) The base point is $(2,1,-4)$ and the direction vector $(3,-1,2)$, giving $\dfrac{x-2}{3}=\dfrac{y-1}{-1}=\dfrac{z+4}{2}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If a component of the direction vector of a line is zero, the symmetric equations:</li>
<li>a) Do not exist for that line</li>
<li>b) Are written by indicating that that coordinate is constant and equating the other two fractions</li>
<li>c) Are replaced by the parametric equations</li>
<li>d) Imply that the line is parallel to all three axes</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) When $d_k = 0$, the $k$-th coordinate is constant and equal to the value of the base point; the other two fractions are equated normally.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.1.4 Converting between Different Forms of the Equation of a Line</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Given the line $r:\;\dfrac{x-1}{2} = \dfrac{y+3}{-1} = \dfrac{z}{4}$, express $r$ in vector form and in parametric form. Then find a second point on $r$ different from the base point.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Step 1: Identify the point and direction vector.</strong></p>
<p>From the symmetric equations: base point $P(1,-3,0)$ and direction vector $\vec{d} = (2,-1,4)$.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2: Vector form.</strong></p>
<p>$$(x,y,z) = (1,-3,0) + \lambda(2,-1,4), \quad \lambda \in \mathbb{R}$$</p>
<p><strong>Step 3: Parametric form.</strong></p>
<p>$$\begin{cases} x = 1 + 2\lambda \ y = -3 - \lambda \ z = 4\lambda \end{cases}$$</p>
<p><strong>Step 4: Second point</strong> (taking $\lambda = 1$):
$$P' = (1+2,\; -3-1,\; 4) = (3,-4,4)$$</p>
<p><strong>Verification:</strong> $\dfrac{3-1}{2} = 1$, $\dfrac{-4+3}{-1} = 1$, $\dfrac{4}{4} = 1$ ✓</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Convert to parametric form the line $r:\;(x,y,z) = (2,-1,5) + \lambda(-3,2,0)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong>
$$\begin{cases} x = 2 - 3\lambda \ y = -1 + 2\lambda \ z = 5 \end{cases}$$
Note that the $z$-component is constant ($z = 5$), which means $r$ is parallel to the $XOY$ plane.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Convert to symmetric equations the line: $\begin{cases} x = -1 + 4t \ y = 2 - t \ z = 3 + 2t \end{cases}$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> We solve for $t$: $t = \dfrac{x+1}{4}$, $t = -(y-2) = \dfrac{y-2}{-1}$, $t = \dfrac{z-3}{2}$.
The symmetric equations are:
$$\frac{x+1}{4} = \frac{y-2}{-1} = \frac{z-3}{2}$$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A line passes through $A(1,2,3)$ and is perpendicular to the plane $\pi:\; 2x - y + 3z = 5$. Write its equations in all three forms (vector, parametric, and symmetric).</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The normal vector to the plane is $\vec{n} = (2,-1,3)$. A line perpendicular to the plane has $\vec{n}$ as its direction vector.
- <strong>Vector:</strong> $(x,y,z) = (1,2,3) + \lambda(2,-1,3)$
- <strong>Parametric:</strong> $x = 1+2\lambda,\; y = 2-\lambda,\; z = 3+3\lambda$
- <strong>Symmetric:</strong> $\dfrac{x-1}{2} = \dfrac{y-2}{-1} = \dfrac{z-3}{3}$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>A line $r$ has symmetric equations $\dfrac{x-a}{2} = \dfrac{y-1}{b} = \dfrac{z+3}{1}$ and passes through the point $Q(4,-1,-2)$. Find $a$ and $b$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Since $Q \in r$, we substitute $Q(4,-1,-2)$:
$$\frac{4-a}{2} = \frac{-1-1}{b} = \frac{-2+3}{1} = 1$$
From the equality with $1$:
- $\dfrac{4-a}{2} = 1 \Rightarrow 4-a = 2 \Rightarrow a = 2$
- $\dfrac{-2}{b} = 1 \Rightarrow b = -2$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The line $r$ is given by the equations $\dfrac{x-2}{1} = \dfrac{y+1}{3} = \dfrac{z-4}{-2}$ and the point $A(4,5,0)$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Write the parametric equations of $r$ and the direction vector.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Find the line $s$ passing through $A$ and parallel to $r$, expressing it in vector and symmetric form.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Check that $A \notin r$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Direction vector $\vec{d}_r = (1,3,-2)$, point $P(2,-1,4)$.
$$r:\;\begin{cases} x = 2 + \lambda \ y = -1 + 3\lambda \ z = 4 - 2\lambda \end{cases}$$</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> $s$ passes through $A(4,5,0)$ with $\vec{d}_s = \vec{d}_r = (1,3,-2)$:
- Vector: $(x,y,z) = (4,5,0) + \mu(1,3,-2)$
- Symmetric: $\dfrac{x-4}{1} = \dfrac{y-5}{3} = \dfrac{z}{-2}$</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> We substitute $A(4,5,0)$ into the symmetric equations of $r$:
$$\frac{4-2}{1} = 2, \quad \frac{5+1}{3} = 2, \quad \frac{0-4}{-2} = 2$$
All three quotients equal $2$, which means $A \in r$. Therefore the calculation should be revised: $A$ does belong.
<strong>Correction note:</strong> $A(4,5,0) \in r$ with $\lambda = 2$: $x=2+2=4$✓, $y=-1+6=5$✓, $z=4-4=0$✓. Therefore $A \in r$ and $s = r$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The line $(x,y,z)=(1,0,-2)+\lambda(3,-2,1)$ expressed in symmetric form is:</li>
<li>a) $\dfrac{x-3}{1}=\dfrac{y+2}{0}=\dfrac{z-1}{-2}$</li>
<li>b) $\dfrac{x-1}{3}=\dfrac{y}{-2}=\dfrac{z+2}{1}$</li>
<li>c) $\dfrac{x+1}{3}=\dfrac{y}{-2}=\dfrac{z-2}{1}$</li>
<li>d) $\dfrac{x-1}{3}=\dfrac{y+2}{-1}=\dfrac{z+2}{1}$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) The base point is $(1,0,-2)$ and the direction vector $(3,-2,1)$, giving $\dfrac{x-1}{3}=\dfrac{y-0}{-2}=\dfrac{z-(-2)}{1} = \dfrac{x-1}{3}=\dfrac{y}{-2}=\dfrac{z+2}{1}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>To convert from symmetric equations to parametric equations, the parameter $\lambda$ is:</li>
<li>a) The value of $x$ at a point on the line</li>
<li>b) The common value of the three equated fractions</li>
<li>c) The distance from the point to the origin</li>
<li>d) The length of the direction vector</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) In the symmetric equations $\dfrac{x-x_0}{d_x}=\dfrac{y-y_0}{d_y}=\dfrac{z-z_0}{d_z}=\lambda$, the parameter $\lambda$ is the common value of the three equated fractions.</p>
</blockquote>
