<h5>5.2.1 Vector Equation of a Plane</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Find the vector equation of the plane passing through $P(1,2,-1)$ with direction vectors $\vec{u} = (1,0,3)$ and $\vec{v} = (0,1,-2)$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>Every plane is determined by a point $P_0$ and two linearly independent direction vectors $\vec{u}$ and $\vec{v}$ (not proportional).</p>
<p>The vector equation is:
$$\vec{r} = \overrightarrow{OP_0} + \lambda\,\vec{u} + \mu\,\vec{v}, \quad \lambda,\mu \in \mathbb{R}$$</p>
<p>In our case:
$$\boxed{(x,y,z) = (1,2,-1) + \lambda(1,0,3) + \mu(0,1,-2), \quad \lambda,\mu \in \mathbb{R}}$$</p>
<p><strong>Check of linear independence:</strong> $\vec{u} \times \vec{v} = \begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\1&amp;0&amp;3\0&amp;1&amp;-2\end{vmatrix} = (0\cdot(-2)-3\cdot1)\vec{i} - (1\cdot(-2)-3\cdot0)\vec{j} + (1\cdot1-0\cdot0)\vec{k} = (-3,2,1) \neq \vec{0}$ ✓</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Write the vector equation of the plane passing through the origin $O(0,0,0)$ with direction vectors $\vec{u}=(1,0,0)$ and $\vec{v}=(0,1,0)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong>
$$(x,y,z) = \lambda(1,0,0) + \mu(0,1,0) = (\lambda, \mu, 0), \quad \lambda,\mu \in \mathbb{R}$$
This is the plane $z=0$, that is, the $XOY$ plane.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Write the vector equation of the plane passing through $A(1,-1,2)$, $B(3,0,1)$ and $C(2,-2,4)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The direction vectors are:
$$\vec{AB} = (2,1,-1), \quad \vec{AC} = (1,-1,2)$$
We check independence: $\vec{AB}$ and $\vec{AC}$ are not proportional ✓
$$(x,y,z) = (1,-1,2) + \lambda(2,1,-1) + \mu(1,-1,2), \quad \lambda,\mu \in \mathbb{R}$$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The plane $\pi$ has vector equation $(x,y,z) = (2,1,3)+\lambda(1,-1,0)+\mu(2,0,1)$. Find a point on the plane for $\lambda=2$, $\mu=-1$ and verify that it belongs to the plane.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> For $\lambda=2$, $\mu=-1$:
$$(x,y,z) = (2,1,3) + 2(1,-1,0) + (-1)(2,0,1) = (2,1,3)+(2,-2,0)+(-2,0,-1) = (2,-1,2)$$
The point $Q(2,-1,2)$ is obtained. To verify it belongs to the plane, there exists $(\lambda,\mu)=(2,-1)$ that generates $Q$ ✓.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Can the vectors $\vec{u}=(1,2,3)$ and $\vec{v}=(2,4,6)$ be the direction vectors of a plane? Justify your answer.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{v} = 2\vec{u}$, so $\vec{u}$ and $\vec{v}$ are <strong>proportional</strong> (linearly dependent). They cannot be the direction vectors of a plane, since any pair of direction vectors must be linearly independent to determine a plane (two proportional vectors determine only a line).</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Consider the points $A(1,0,2)$, $B(2,1,0)$ and $C(0,-1,3)$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Find the vector equation of the plane $\pi$ passing through $A$, $B$ and $C$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Verify that $D(3,2,-2)$ belongs to $\pi$ (find suitable $\lambda$ and $\mu$).</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $\vec{AB} = (1,1,-2)$, $\vec{AC} = (-1,-1,1)$.
But $\vec{AC} = -\vec{AB}$... we check: $(-1,-1,1) \neq k(1,1,-2)$ for any single real $k$... $-1 = k$, $-1=k$ ✓, $1 = -2k = 2$ ✗. They are not proportional.
$$(x,y,z) = (1,0,2) + \lambda(1,1,-2) + \mu(-1,-1,1)$$
Note: $\vec{AB}$ and $\vec{AC}$: $(-1,-1,1) = -1\cdot(1,1,-1)$, they are linearly dependent only if $(1,1,-2)\parallel(-1,-1,1)$: $-1/1=-1/1=1/(-2)$? $-1\neq -1/2$. So <strong>they are not proportional</strong> ✓.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> System: $(1,0,2)+\lambda(1,1,-2)+\mu(-1,-1,1)=(3,2,-2)$
$$\lambda - \mu = 2 \quad (I)$$
$$\lambda - \mu = 2 \quad (II)$$
$$-2\lambda + \mu = -4 \quad (III)$$
From $(I)$: $\mu = \lambda - 2$. Substituting into $(III)$: $-2\lambda + \lambda - 2 = -4 \Rightarrow \lambda = 2$, $\mu = 0$.
Verification: $(1,0,2)+2(1,1,-2)=(3,2,-2)$ ✓. Therefore $D \in \pi$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The vector equation of a plane contains:</li>
<li>a) One point and one direction vector</li>
<li>b) Two points and one direction vector</li>
<li>c) One point and two linearly independent direction vectors</li>
<li>d) Three direction vectors</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) The vector equation of a plane $\vec{r} = \vec{r_0} + \lambda\vec{u} + \mu\vec{v}$ requires a point $P_0$ (giving $\vec{r_0}$) and two linearly independent direction vectors $\vec{u}$, $\vec{v}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The plane with vector equation $(x,y,z)=(1,2,3)+\lambda(1,0,0)+\mu(0,1,0)$ is:</li>
<li>a) The plane $z=0$</li>
<li>b) The plane $z=3$</li>
<li>c) The plane $x+y=3$</li>
<li>d) The plane $x=1$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) Expanding: $x=1+\lambda$, $y=2+\mu$, $z=3$. The $z$-coordinate is always $3$, so it is the plane $z=3$.</p>
</blockquote>
