<h5>5.2.2 General (Implicit) Equation of a Plane. Normal Vector</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Find the general equation of the plane $\pi$ passing through $A(1,-1,2)$ with normal vector $\vec{n} = (3,-2,1)$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>The general equation of a plane with normal vector $\vec{n} = (a,b,c)$ passing through the point $P_0(x_0,y_0,z_0)$ is:</p>
<p>$$a(x-x_0) + b(y-y_0) + c(z-z_0) = 0$$</p>
<p>Substituting $\vec{n}=(3,-2,1)$ and $A(1,-1,2)$:
$$3(x-1) - 2(y-(-1)) + 1(z-2) = 0$$
$$3x - 3 - 2y - 2 + z - 2 = 0$$
$$\boxed{3x - 2y + z - 7 = 0}$$</p>
<p><strong>Verification:</strong> $3(1)-2(-1)+2-7 = 3+2+2-7 = 0$ ✓</p>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> The normal vector is read directly from the coefficients $(a,b,c)$ of the general equation $ax+by+cz+d=0$.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the general equation of the plane passing through $P(0,0,0)$ with normal vector $\vec{n}=(1,2,3)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong>
$$1(x-0)+2(y-0)+3(z-0)=0 \Rightarrow \boxed{x+2y+3z=0}$$
This plane passes through the origin.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Identify the normal vector of the plane $\pi:\; 2x - 5y + z + 4 = 0$ and a point on the plane.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong>
- <strong>Normal vector:</strong> $\vec{n} = (2,-5,1)$ (coefficients of $x$, $y$, $z$).
- <strong>Point on the plane:</strong> we find a point satisfying the equation. Taking $x=0,y=0$: $z=-4$. Point: $(0,0,-4)$.
<strong>Verification:</strong> $0-0-4+4=0$ ✓.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the equation of the plane passing through $A(2,0,1)$ and $B(1,3,-1)$ and perpendicular to the plane $\pi_0:\; x-y+2z=3$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Let $\vec{n}=(a,b,c)$ be the normal to the desired plane. Conditions:
1. $\overrightarrow{AB} = (-1,3,-2)$ is parallel to the desired plane, so $\vec{n} \perp \overrightarrow{AB}$: $-a+3b-2c=0$.
2. The plane is perpendicular to $\pi_0$, which has normal $\vec{n}_0=(1,-1,2)$. The normals are perpendicular: $\vec{n}\cdot\vec{n}_0=0$: $a-b+2c=0$.
System: $-a+3b-2c=0$ and $a-b+2c=0$. Adding: $2b=0 \Rightarrow b=0$.
From the second: $a+2c=0 \Rightarrow a=-2c$. Taking $c=1$: $a=-2$, $b=0$.
$\vec{n}=(-2,0,1)$. The plane passes through $A(2,0,1)$:
$$-2(x-2)+0(y-0)+1(z-1)=0 \Rightarrow -2x+4+z-1=0 \Rightarrow \boxed{-2x+z+3=0}$$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find the value of $k$ such that the plane $\pi_1:\; kx - 2y + z = 3$ is perpendicular to the plane $\pi_2:\; x + ky + 2z = 0$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The normal vectors are $\vec{n}_1=(k,-2,1)$ and $\vec{n}_2=(1,k,2)$.
Perpendicularity $\Leftrightarrow \vec{n}_1\cdot\vec{n}_2=0$:
$$k\cdot1 + (-2)\cdot k + 1\cdot 2 = 0 \Rightarrow k - 2k + 2 = 0 \Rightarrow -k + 2 = 0 \Rightarrow k = 2$$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Let the plane $\pi:\; 2x + y - 3z + 6 = 0$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Find the normal vector to $\pi$ and a point on $\pi$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Determine the equation of the plane $\sigma$ parallel to $\pi$ passing through $Q(1,0,2)$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Calculate the distance between $\pi$ and $\sigma$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $\vec{n} = (2,1,-3)$. Point: with $x=0,y=0$: $-3z=-6 \Rightarrow z=2$. Point: $(0,0,2)$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> $\sigma \parallel \pi$ $\Rightarrow$ same normal vector $\vec{n}=(2,1,-3)$.
$$\sigma:\; 2(x-1)+1(y-0)-3(z-2)=0 \Rightarrow 2x+y-3z+4=0$$</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Distance between parallel planes $ax+by+cz+d_1=0$ and $ax+by+cz+d_2=0$:
$$d = \frac{|d_1-d_2|}{\sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}} = \frac{|6-4|}{\sqrt{4+1+9}} = \frac{2}{\sqrt{14}} = \frac{2\sqrt{14}}{14} = \frac{\sqrt{14}}{7}$$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The normal vector to the plane $3x - y + 2z - 5 = 0$ is:</li>
<li>a) $(3,-1,2,-5)$</li>
<li>b) $(-3,1,-2)$</li>
<li>c) $(3,-1,2)$</li>
<li>d) $(3,1,2)$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) The normal vector is read from the coefficients of $x$, $y$, $z$: $\vec{n}=(3,-1,2)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If two planes have proportional normal vectors, then:</li>
<li>a) They are perpendicular</li>
<li>b) They are parallel or coincident</li>
<li>c) They intersect in a line</li>
<li>d) They intersect at a point</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) If $\vec{n}_1 = k\vec{n}_2$, the planes are parallel (if distinct) or coincident (if the same). The intersection condition requires that the normals are not proportional.</p>
</blockquote>
