<h5>5.2.3 Determining the Equation of a Plane Given Three Points</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Determine the general equation of the plane passing through the points $A(1,0,0)$, $B(0,2,0)$ and $C(0,0,3)$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Method using the normal vector via the cross product:</strong></p>
<p>$\vec{AB} = (-1,2,0)$, $\vec{AC} = (-1,0,3)$.</p>
<p>The normal vector is $\vec{n} = \vec{AB} \times \vec{AC}$:</p>
<p>$$\vec{n} = \begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\-1&amp;2&amp;0\-1&amp;0&amp;3\end{vmatrix} = (2\cdot3 - 0\cdot0)\vec{i} - ((-1)\cdot3 - 0\cdot(-1))\vec{j} + ((-1)\cdot0 - 2\cdot(-1))\vec{k}$$
$$= (6)\vec{i} - (-3)\vec{j} + (2)\vec{k} = (6,3,2)$$</p>
<p>The plane passes through $A(1,0,0)$ with normal $(6,3,2)$:
$$6(x-1)+3(y-0)+2(z-0)=0 \Rightarrow \boxed{6x+3y+2z-6=0}$$</p>
<p><strong>Verification:</strong> $A$: $6-6=0$ ✓; $B$: $0+6+0-6=0$ ✓; $C$: $0+0+6-6=0$ ✓.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the equation of the plane passing through $A(1,1,0)$, $B(0,1,1)$ and $C(1,0,1)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{AB}=(-1,0,1)$, $\vec{AC}=(0,-1,1)$.
$$\vec{n} = \vec{AB}\times\vec{AC} = \begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\-1&amp;0&amp;1\0&amp;-1&amp;1\end{vmatrix} = (0\cdot1-1\cdot(-1))\vec{i}-((-1)\cdot1-1\cdot0)\vec{j}+((-1)(-1)-0\cdot0)\vec{k}$$
$= (1)\vec{i}-(-1)\vec{j}+(1)\vec{k} = (1,1,1)$
Plane through $A(1,1,0)$: $(x-1)+(y-1)+z=0 \Rightarrow \boxed{x+y+z-2=0}$
Verification: $A$: $1+1+0-2=0$✓, $B$: $0+1+1-2=0$✓, $C$: $1+0+1-2=0$✓.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find the equation of the plane passing through $A(2,0,0)$, $B(0,3,0)$ and $C(0,0,1)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{AB}=(-2,3,0)$, $\vec{AC}=(-2,0,1)$.
$$\vec{n}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\-2&amp;3&amp;0\-2&amp;0&amp;1\end{vmatrix}=(3\cdot1-0\cdot0)\vec{i}-((-2)\cdot1-0\cdot(-2))\vec{j}+((-2)\cdot0-3\cdot(-2))\vec{k}=(3,2,6)$$
Through $A(2,0,0)$: $3(x-2)+2y+6z=0 \Rightarrow \boxed{3x+2y+6z-6=0}$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the plane determined by the points $P(1,-1,0)$, $Q(2,1,3)$ and $R(-1,0,1)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{PQ}=(1,2,3)$, $\vec{PR}=(-2,1,1)$.
$$\vec{n}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\1&amp;2&amp;3\-2&amp;1&amp;1\end{vmatrix}=(2-3)\vec{i}-(1+6)\vec{j}+(1+4)\vec{k}=(-1,-7,5)$$
Through $P(1,-1,0)$: $-(x-1)-7(y+1)+5z=0 \Rightarrow -x+1-7y-7+5z=0$
$$\boxed{-x-7y+5z-6=0} \quad \text{or equivalently}\quad x+7y-5z+6=0$$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Three points on the plane $\pi:\; ax+2y-z=3$ are $A(1,1,0)$, $B(t,0,1)$ and $C(0,-1,k)$. Find $t$ and $k$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> We substitute each point into $ax+2y-z=3$... first we determine $a$ using $A$:
$a(1)+2(1)-0=3 \Rightarrow a=1$.
The plane is $x+2y-z=3$.
For $B(t,0,1)$: $t+0-1=3 \Rightarrow t=4$.
For $C(0,-1,k)$: $0-2-k=3 \Rightarrow k=-5$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Given the points $A(2,1,-1)$, $B(0,3,2)$ and $C(-1,2,1)$:</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Find the equation of the plane $\pi$ containing $A$, $B$ and $C$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Determine whether the point $D(1,6,5)$ belongs to $\pi$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Find the equation of the plane $\sigma$ parallel to $\pi$ passing through the origin.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $\vec{AB}=(-2,2,3)$, $\vec{AC}=(-3,1,2)$.
$$\vec{n}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\-2&amp;2&amp;3\-3&amp;1&amp;2\end{vmatrix}=(4-3)\vec{i}-(-4+9)\vec{j}+(-2+6)\vec{k}=(1,-5,4)$$
Through $A(2,1,-1)$: $(x-2)-5(y-1)+4(z+1)=0$
$$x-2-5y+5+4z+4=0 \Rightarrow \boxed{x-5y+4z+7=0}$$</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> $D(1,6,5)$: $1-30+20+7=-2\neq0$. $D \notin \pi$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> $\sigma \parallel \pi$ with the same normal vector $(1,-5,4)$, passing through $O(0,0,0)$:
$\boxed{x-5y+4z=0}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>To find the equation of the plane through three points, the most systematic method is:</li>
<li>a) Compute the dot product of two vectors in the plane</li>
<li>b) Compute the cross product of two vectors in the plane to obtain the normal vector</li>
<li>c) Compute the scalar triple product of three vectors</li>
<li>d) Use Sarrus's rule directly with the coordinates of the three points</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) The cross product $\vec{AB}\times\vec{AC}$ gives the normal vector to the plane, which is then used in the point-normal equation.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If three points are collinear (lie on the same line), when trying to determine the plane through them:</li>
<li>a) A unique plane is obtained</li>
<li>b) Infinitely many planes are obtained</li>
<li>c) No plane exists</li>
<li>d) Exactly two planes are obtained</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) If the three points are collinear, $\vec{AB}$ and $\vec{AC}$ are proportional, the cross product is $\vec{0}$, and there are infinitely many planes containing that line.</p>
</blockquote>
