<h5>5.2.4 Planes Parallel to the Coordinate Axes and to Each Other</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Classify the planes $\pi_1:\; 3x - 6y + 9z = 12$, $\pi_2:\; x - 2y + 3z = 5$ and $\pi_3:\; y - z = 2$ indicating whether they are parallel to any coordinate axis or plane.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>$\pi_1$ and $\pi_2$:</strong> The normal vectors are $\vec{n}_1 = (3,-6,9)$ and $\vec{n}_2 = (1,-2,3)$. We observe that $\vec{n}_1 = 3\vec{n}_2$, so they are proportional: the planes are <strong>parallel or coincident</strong>.</p>
<p>We take a point of $\pi_2$ (e.g., $x=y=0 \Rightarrow 3z=5 \Rightarrow z=5/3$: the point $(0,0,5/3)$) and substitute into $\pi_1$: $3(0)-6(0)+9(5/3) = 15 \neq 12$. They are <strong>distinct parallel planes</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>$\pi_3:\; y - z = 2$</strong> has normal vector $\vec{n}_3 = (0,1,-1)$. Since the $x$-component is zero, $\pi_3$ does not contain the $OX$ axis... but $\vec{n}_3 \perp \vec{e}_1 = (1,0,0)$, which means $\pi_3$ <strong>contains the direction of the $OX$ axis</strong>: it is parallel to the $OX$ axis.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Write the equation of the plane parallel to the $XOY$ plane passing through the point $P(1,2,5)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The $XOY$ plane has equation $z=0$. A plane parallel to $XOY$ has the form $z=k$. Since it passes through $P(1,2,5)$: $k=5$.
$$\boxed{z = 5}$$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>What is the equation of the plane containing the $OZ$ axis and the point $A(1,-1,0)$?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The plane contains the $OZ$ axis, so it contains the vectors $\vec{k}=(0,0,1)$ and $\vec{OA}=(1,-1,0)$.
Normal vector: $\vec{n} = \vec{k}\times\vec{OA} = \begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\0&amp;0&amp;1\1&amp;-1&amp;0\end{vmatrix} = (0\cdot0-1\cdot(-1))\vec{i}-(0\cdot0-1\cdot1)\vec{j}+(0\cdot(-1)-0\cdot1)\vec{k} = (1,1,0)$.
Plane through the origin with $\vec{n}=(1,1,0)$: $\boxed{x+y=0}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the equation of the plane parallel to $\pi:\; 2x-y+3z=7$ at distance $\sqrt{14}$ from $\pi$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> A plane parallel to $\pi$ has the form $2x-y+3z=k$. The distance between two parallel planes $2x-y+3z=7$ and $2x-y+3z=k$ is:
$$d = \frac{|k-7|}{\sqrt{4+1+9}} = \frac{|k-7|}{\sqrt{14}} = \sqrt{14}$$
$|k-7| = 14 \Rightarrow k = 21$ or $k = -7$.
The two desired planes are: $\boxed{2x-y+3z=21}$ and $\boxed{2x-y+3z=-7}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Classify the following planes according to their position relative to the coordinate axes:</li>
<li>$\alpha:\; x = 3$</li>
<li>$\beta:\; 2y + z = 0$</li>
<li>$\gamma:\; x + y = 4$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong>
- $\alpha:\;x=3$: normal vector $(1,0,0)=\vec{i}$. The plane is <strong>perpendicular to the $OX$ axis</strong> and <strong>parallel to the $YOZ$ plane</strong>.
- $\beta:\;2y+z=0$: normal $(0,2,1)$. The $x$-component is zero, so $\vec{e}_1\perp\vec{n}$: <strong>contains the $OX$ axis</strong> (is parallel to $OX$).
- $\gamma:\;x+y=4$: normal $(1,1,0)$. The $z$-component is zero: <strong>parallel to the $OZ$ axis</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Let the plane $\pi:\; x+2y-2z=6$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Is $\pi$ parallel to any coordinate axis? Justify your answer.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Find the two planes parallel to $\pi$ at distance $3$ from $\pi$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Find the intersection point of $\pi$ with the $OX$ axis.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> The normal vector of $\pi$ is $\vec{n}=(1,2,-2)$. For $\pi$ to be parallel to the $OX$ axis, we would need $\vec{n}\cdot(1,0,0)=0$, i.e. $1=0$: <strong>false</strong>. Similarly for $OY$: $\vec{n}\cdot(0,1,0)=2\neq0$, and for $OZ$: $\vec{n}\cdot(0,0,1)=-2\neq0$. $\pi$ <strong>is not parallel to any coordinate axis</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Parallel planes: $x+2y-2z=k$. Distance to $\pi$:
$$\frac{|k-6|}{\sqrt{1+4+4}}=\frac{|k-6|}{3}=3 \Rightarrow |k-6|=9 \Rightarrow k=15 \text{ or } k=-3$$
The planes are $\boxed{x+2y-2z=15}$ and $\boxed{x+2y-2z=-3}$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> The $OX$ axis has equations $y=0$, $z=0$. Substituting into $\pi$:
$x+0-0=6 \Rightarrow x=6$. Intersection point: $\boxed{(6,0,0)}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Which of the following planes is parallel to the $OY$ axis?</li>
<li>a) $x+y+z=1$</li>
<li>b) $y=2$</li>
<li>c) $x-z=3$</li>
<li>d) $x+y=5$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) For the plane to be parallel to the $OY$ axis, its normal vector $\vec{n}$ must be perpendicular to $\vec{j}=(0,1,0)$, i.e., the $y$-component of the normal must be $0$. The plane $x-z=3$ has $\vec{n}=(1,0,-1)$, with zero $y$-component ✓.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Two planes $\pi_1:\;ax+by+cz=d_1$ and $\pi_2:\;ax+by+cz=d_2$ (with $d_1\neq d_2$) are:</li>
<li>a) Perpendicular</li>
<li>b) Intersecting</li>
<li>c) Parallel and distinct</li>
<li>d) Coincident</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) They have the same normal vector (same coefficients $a,b,c$), so they are parallel. Since $d_1\neq d_2$, they are not the same plane: they are <strong>parallel and distinct</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<hr />
<h5>5.3.1 Relative Position of Two Lines</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Study the relative position of the lines:
$$r:\;\frac{x-1}{2}=\frac{y+1}{-1}=\frac{z}{1} \qquad s:\;\frac{x-3}{4}=\frac{y+3}{-2}=\frac{z-2}{2}$$</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Step 1: Direction vectors.</strong>
$\vec{d}_r=(2,-1,1)$, $\vec{d}_s=(4,-2,2)=2(2,-1,1)=2\vec{d}_r$.</p>
<p>The vectors are proportional: the lines are <strong>parallel or coincident</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2: Check whether they are the same line.</strong></p>
<p>We take a point of $s$: $P_s=(3,-3,2)$. Is it on $r$?</p>
<p>$$\frac{3-1}{2}=1, \quad \frac{-3+1}{-1}=2, \quad \frac{2}{1}=2$$</p>
<p>The values are not equal ($1\neq 2$), therefore $P_s \notin r$.</p>
<p><strong>Conclusion: $r$ and $s$ are distinct parallel lines.</strong></p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Determine whether the lines $r:\,(x,y,z)=(1,0,2)+\lambda(1,-1,3)$ and $s:\,(x,y,z)=(3,-2,8)+\mu(2,-2,6)$ are parallel, coincident, intersecting, or skew.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{d}_r=(1,-1,3)$, $\vec{d}_s=(2,-2,6)=2\vec{d}_r$. They are proportional: parallel or coincident.
Point of $s$: $Q(3,-2,8)$. Is $Q\in r$? $(3-1)/1=2$, $(-2-0)/(-1)=2$, $(8-2)/3=2$. All three equal $2$: $Q\in r$ ✓.
The lines are <strong>coincident</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Determine the relative position of $r:\;x=1+t,\;y=-t,\;z=2+t$ and $s:\;x=2+2\mu,\;y=1-\mu,\;z=3-\mu$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{d}_r=(1,-1,1)$, $\vec{d}_s=(2,-1,-1)$. Not proportional ($2/1\neq -1/-1$). We equate:
$1+t=2+2\mu$, $-t=1-\mu$, $2+t=3-\mu$.
From the second: $t=\mu-1$. From the third: $t=-\mu+1 \Rightarrow \mu-1=-\mu+1 \Rightarrow 2\mu=2 \Rightarrow \mu=1$, $t=0$.
We check in the first: $1+0=1$, $2+2=4$. $1\neq 4$: <strong>inconsistent</strong>.
The direction vectors are not proportional and they do not intersect: <strong>skew lines</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Study the relative position of $r:\;\dfrac{x}{1}=\dfrac{y-1}{2}=\dfrac{z+1}{-1}$ and $s:\;\dfrac{x-2}{a}=\dfrac{y+1}{4}=\dfrac{z-1}{-2}$ depending on the value of the parameter $a$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{d}_r=(1,2,-1)$, $\vec{d}_s=(a,4,-2)$.
For parallelism: $(a,4,-2)=k(1,2,-1) \Rightarrow 4=2k \Rightarrow k=2 \Rightarrow a=2$, and $-2=k\cdot(-1)=-2$ ✓. So for $a=2$: parallel or coincident.
<strong>With $a=2$:</strong> point of $s$: $(2,-1,1)$. Does it belong to $r$? $\lambda=2/1=2$; $y: 1+2\cdot2=5\neq-1$. Does not belong: <strong>distinct parallel lines</strong>.
<strong>With $a\neq2$:</strong> $\vec{d}_r$ and $\vec{d}_s$ are not proportional. We solve the intersection system.
$t=2+a\mu$, $1+2t=-1+4\mu$, $-1-t=1-2\mu$.
From the third: $t=2\mu-2$. From the first: $2\mu-2=2+a\mu \Rightarrow (2-a)\mu=4$.
If $a\neq2$: $\mu=\dfrac{4}{2-a}$, $t=\dfrac{8}{2-a}-2$.
We check in the second equation (left as an exercise). In general, for $a\neq2$ the lines are <strong>skew</strong> or <strong>intersecting</strong> depending on whether the $3\times2$ system is consistent.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Lines $r$ and $s$ are intersecting and meet at $P(2,1,-1)$. If $\vec{d}_r=(1,-1,2)$ and $\vec{d}_s=(3,1,0)$, write the equations of both lines.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong>
$$r:\;(x,y,z)=(2,1,-1)+\lambda(1,-1,2)$$
$$s:\;(x,y,z)=(2,1,-1)+\mu(3,1,0)$$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Study the relative position of the lines:
   $$r:\;\begin{cases}x=2+t\y=-1+2t\z=3-t\end{cases} \qquad s:\;\begin{cases}x=4+\mu\y=3-\mu\z=1+\mu\end{cases}$$
   If they intersect, find the intersection point and the angle they form.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Direction vectors:</strong> $\vec{d}_r=(1,2,-1)$, $\vec{d}_s=(1,-1,1)$. Not proportional.</p>
<p><strong>Intersection system:</strong>
$$2+t=4+\mu \Rightarrow t-\mu=2 \quad (I)$$
$$-1+2t=3-\mu \Rightarrow 2t+\mu=4 \quad (II)$$
$$3-t=1+\mu \Rightarrow t+\mu=2 \quad (III)$$
From $(I)$ and $(III)$: adding $(t-\mu)+(t+\mu)=4 \Rightarrow 2t=4 \Rightarrow t=2$, $\mu=0$.
Verification in $(II)$: $4+0=4$ ✓.
<strong>Intersection point</strong> ($t=2$): $x=4$, $y=3$, $z=1$. Point: $\mathbf{P(4,3,1)}$.</p>
<p><strong>Angle:</strong>
$$\cos\theta = \frac{|\vec{d}_r\cdot\vec{d}_s|}{|\vec{d}_r||\vec{d}_s|} = \frac{|1\cdot1+2\cdot(-1)+(-1)\cdot1|}{\sqrt{1+4+1}\cdot\sqrt{1+1+1}} = \frac{|1-2-1|}{\sqrt{6}\cdot\sqrt{3}} = \frac{2}{\sqrt{18}} = \frac{2}{3\sqrt{2}} = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{3}$$
$$\theta = \arccos!\left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{3}\right) \approx 61{,}87°$$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Two lines in space with non-proportional direction vectors:</li>
<li>a) Are always intersecting</li>
<li>b) Are always parallel</li>
<li>c) Can be intersecting or skew, but not parallel or coincident</li>
<li>d) Are always skew</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) If the direction vectors are not proportional, the lines are neither parallel nor coincident. They can be intersecting (meeting at a point) or skew (not meeting and not parallel).</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>To determine whether two lines with non-proportional direction vectors are intersecting or skew, one must:</li>
<li>a) Calculate the angle between them</li>
<li>b) Set up the system of equal points and check whether it has a solution</li>
<li>c) Calculate the cross product of their direction vectors</li>
<li>d) Calculate the distance between their base points</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) We set up the system by equating the coordinates of the generic points on each line; if the $3\times2$ system is consistent, the lines intersect; if not, they are skew.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.3.2 Relative Position of a Line and a Plane</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Study the relative position of the line $r:\;x=1+2t,\;y=-1+t,\;z=3-t$ and the plane $\pi:\;2x-y+3z=10$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Method:</strong> Substitute the parametric equations of $r$ into the equation of $\pi$.</p>
<p>$$2(1+2t) - (-1+t) + 3(3-t) = 10$$
$$2+4t+1-t+9-3t = 10$$
$$12 + 0t = 10$$
$$12 = 10 \quad \text{(Contradiction)}$$</p>
<p>No value of $t$ satisfies the equation. This means the line <strong>does not intersect</strong> the plane.</p>
<p>Since $\vec{d}<em>r=(2,1,-1)$ and $\vec{n}</em>\pi=(2,-1,3)$:
$$\vec{d}<em>r\cdot\vec{n}</em>\pi = 4-1-3 = 0$$</p>
<p>The direction vector is perpendicular to the normal of the plane, so $r$ is <strong>parallel</strong> to $\pi$ (and since it has no point in $\pi$: <strong>parallel without being contained</strong>).</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Study the position of $r:\;(x,y,z)=(1,2,3)+\lambda(1,1,1)$ relative to the plane $\pi:\;x+y+z=6$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Substituting: $(1+\lambda)+(2+\lambda)+(3+\lambda)=6 \Rightarrow 6+3\lambda=6 \Rightarrow \lambda=0$.
A solution exists ($\lambda=0$). The intersection point is $(1,2,3)$.
Since $\vec{d}\cdot\vec{n}=1+1+1=3\neq0$, the line <strong>intersects the plane</strong>. Intersection: $(1,2,3)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Determine whether the line $r:\;\dfrac{x-1}{1}=\dfrac{y-2}{-2}=\dfrac{z}{1}$ is contained in the plane $\pi:\;x-2y+z+2=0$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> We check two conditions:
1. The base point $(1,2,0)$: $1-4+0+2=-1\neq0$. The base point <strong>does not belong</strong> to $\pi$, so the line is not contained.
(Additionally: $\vec{d}\cdot\vec{n}=1\cdot1+(-2)(-2)+1\cdot1=1+4+1=6\neq0$: the line is not parallel to the plane, it is <strong>intersecting</strong>.)</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the intersection point of $r:\;\dfrac{x-2}{1}=\dfrac{y+1}{2}=\dfrac{z-3}{-1}=\lambda$ with the plane $\pi:\;3x-y+2z=11$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Parametric equations: $x=2+\lambda$, $y=-1+2\lambda$, $z=3-\lambda$.
Substituting into $\pi$:
$$3(2+\lambda)-(-1+2\lambda)+2(3-\lambda)=11$$
$$6+3\lambda+1-2\lambda+6-2\lambda=11$$
$$13-\lambda=11 \Rightarrow \lambda=2$$
Point: $x=4$, $y=3$, $z=1$. <strong>Intersection: $(4,3,1)$</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find the values of $m$ such that the line $r:\;x=m+t,\;y=1-t,\;z=2+mt$ is parallel to the plane $\pi:\;2x+y+z=5$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> For $r \parallel \pi$, the direction vector $\vec{d}=(m,-1,m)$ must be perpendicular to the normal $\vec{n}=(2,1,1)$:
$$\vec{d}\cdot\vec{n}=2m-1+m=3m-1=0 \Rightarrow m=\frac{1}{3}$$
We also need to verify that the line is not contained. With $m=1/3$: base point $(1/3,1,2)$ in $\pi$: $2/3+1+2=11/3\neq5$. The line is <strong>parallel</strong> (not contained) for $m=\dfrac{1}{3}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Given the line $r:\;\dfrac{x-1}{2}=\dfrac{y}{-1}=\dfrac{z+2}{3}$ and the plane $\pi:\;ax-y+z=b$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> For $a=1$, $b=3$: find the intersection point of $r$ with $\pi$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Find $a$ and $b$ such that $r$ is contained in $\pi$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $a=1,b=3$: parametric equations $x=1+2\lambda$, $y=-\lambda$, $z=-2+3\lambda$.
$(1+2\lambda)-(-\lambda)+(-2+3\lambda)=3$
$1+2\lambda+\lambda-2+3\lambda=3$
$-1+6\lambda=3 \Rightarrow \lambda=\frac{2}{3}$
Point: $x=7/3$, $y=-2/3$, $z=0$. Intersection: $\left(\dfrac{7}{3},-\dfrac{2}{3},0\right)$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> For $r \subset \pi$, we need:
- $\vec{d}<em>r \perp \vec{n}</em>\pi$: $(2,-1,3)\cdot(a,-1,1)=0 \Rightarrow 2a+1+3=0 \Rightarrow a=-2$.
- The base point $(1,0,-2)$ of $r$ belongs to $\pi$: $-2(1)-0+(-2)=b \Rightarrow b=-4$.
<strong>Solution:</strong> $a=-2$, $b=-4$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The condition for a line with direction vector $\vec{d}$ to be parallel to a plane with normal vector $\vec{n}$ is:</li>
<li>a) $\vec{d}\times\vec{n}=\vec{0}$</li>
<li>b) $\vec{d}\cdot\vec{n}=0$</li>
<li>c) $\vec{d}=\vec{n}$</li>
<li>d) $|\vec{d}|=|\vec{n}|$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) The line is parallel to the plane (or contained in it) if and only if its direction vector is perpendicular to the normal vector of the plane: $\vec{d}\cdot\vec{n}=0$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If substituting the parametric equations of a line into the equation of the plane gives $0=0$:</li>
<li>a) The line is parallel to the plane</li>
<li>b) The line does not intersect the plane</li>
<li>c) The line is contained in the plane</li>
<li>d) The line is perpendicular to the plane</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) $0=0$ is a true identity for all values of the parameter, which means all points on the line satisfy the equation of the plane: the line is contained in the plane.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.3.3 Relative Position of Two Planes</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Study the relative position of the planes $\pi_1:\; 2x - y + 3z = 5$ and $\pi_2:\; 4x - 2y + 6z = 8$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>The normal vectors are $\vec{n}_1=(2,-1,3)$ and $\vec{n}_2=(4,-2,6)=2(2,-1,3)=2\vec{n}_1$.</p>
<p>The normals are <strong>proportional</strong>, so the planes are parallel or coincident.</p>
<p>To distinguish: we divide the equation of $\pi_2$ by $2$: $2x-y+3z=4$.</p>
<p>Comparing with $\pi_1:\;2x-y+3z=5$. Since $4\neq5$, the planes are <strong>parallel and distinct</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Distance between them:</strong>
$$d = \frac{|5-4|}{\sqrt{4+1+9}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{14}} = \frac{\sqrt{14}}{14}$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Determine the relative position of $\pi_1:\;x+2y-z=3$ and $\pi_2:\;2x+4y-2z=6$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{n}_2=(2,4,-2)=2(1,2,-1)=2\vec{n}_1$. Dividing $\pi_2$ by $2$: $x+2y-z=3=\pi_1$. The planes are <strong>coincident</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Determine whether the planes $\pi_1:\;x-y+z=2$ and $\pi_2:\;x+y-z=0$ are parallel, coincident, or intersecting.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{n}_1=(1,-1,1)$ and $\vec{n}_2=(1,1,-1)$. Are they proportional? $1/1=1$, $-1/1=-1\neq1$. <strong>Not proportional</strong>: the planes are <strong>intersecting</strong> (they meet in a line).</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the line of intersection of the planes $\pi_1:\;x+y+z=3$ and $\pi_2:\;x-y+2z=1$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The planes are intersecting (normals not proportional). We solve the system:
$$\begin{cases}x+y+z=3\x-y+2z=1\end{cases}$$
Adding: $2x+3z=4 \Rightarrow x=\dfrac{4-3z}{2}$. From the first: $y=3-x-z=3-\dfrac{4-3z}{2}-z=\dfrac{6-4+3z-2z}{2}=\dfrac{2+z}{2}$.
Taking $z=t$ as the parameter: $x=2-\dfrac{3t}{2}$, $y=1+\dfrac{t}{2}$, $z=t$. Multiplying by $2$: $t=2s$:
$$x=2-3s, \quad y=1+s, \quad z=2s$$
Direction vector: $(-3,1,2)$, point: $(2,1,0)$.
The line of intersection is: $\dfrac{x-2}{-3}=\dfrac{y-1}{1}=\dfrac{z}{2}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find the value of $k$ such that the plane $\pi_k:\;2x+ky-z=3$ is parallel to the plane $\pi:\;4x-6y+2z=1$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{n}_\pi=(4,-6,2)=2(2,-3,1)$. For parallelism: $(2,k,-1)=\lambda(2,-3,1)$.
$2=2\lambda \Rightarrow \lambda=1$; $k=-3\lambda=-3$; $-1=\lambda=1$ ✗. Contradiction in the third component. Revisiting: $(2,k,-1)$ proportional to $(4,-6,2)$: $2/4=k/(-6)=(-1)/2$. $1/2=k/(-6) \Rightarrow k=-3$; and $-1/2=-1/2$ ✓. <strong>$k=-3$</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Consider the planes:
   $$\pi_1:\; x + 2y - z = 3, \qquad \pi_2:\; 2x - y + az = b, \qquad \pi_3:\; x + y + z = 2$$</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> For $a=1$, $b=0$: study the relative position of $\pi_1$ and $\pi_2$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Find the line of intersection of $\pi_1$ and $\pi_3$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $\vec{n}_1=(1,2,-1)$, $\vec{n}_2=(2,-1,1)$. Not proportional ($1/2\neq 2/(-1)$): <strong>intersecting</strong>.
System: $x+2y-z=3$ and $2x-y+z=0$.
Adding: $3x+y=3$. From the second: $z=y-2x$.
Taking $x=s$: $y=3-3s$, $z=3-3s-2s=3-5s$.
Line of intersection: $(x,y,z)=(0,3,3)+s(1,-3,-5)$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> $\pi_1: x+2y-z=3$ and $\pi_3: x+y+z=2$. Subtracting: $y-2z=1 \Rightarrow y=1+2z$.
From $\pi_3$: $x=2-y-z=2-(1+2z)-z=1-3z$.
Taking $z=t$: $x=1-3t$, $y=1+2t$, $z=t$.
Line: $(x,y,z)=(1,1,0)+t(-3,2,1)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Two planes in space with non-proportional normal vectors:</li>
<li>a) Are always coincident</li>
<li>b) Are always parallel</li>
<li>c) Meet in exactly one line</li>
<li>d) Can be parallel or intersecting</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) If the normal vectors are not proportional, the planes necessarily intersect, and the intersection is always a line (in $\mathbb{R}^3$).</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The distance between the planes $x+y-z=2$ and $x+y-z=5$ is:</li>
<li>a) $3$</li>
<li>b) $\dfrac{3}{\sqrt{3}} = \sqrt{3}$</li>
<li>c) $\sqrt{3}$</li>
<li>d) $\dfrac{3}{\sqrt{2}}$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) $d=\dfrac{|2-5|}{\sqrt{1+1+1}}=\dfrac{3}{\sqrt{3}}=\sqrt{3}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.3.4 Relative Position of Three Planes</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Study the relative position of the three planes:
$$\pi_1:\; x+y+z=3, \quad \pi_2:\; x-y+z=1, \quad \pi_3:\; 2x+y+3z=7$$</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>The position of three planes is determined by studying the system:
$$\begin{pmatrix}1&amp;1&amp;1\1&amp;-1&amp;1\2&amp;1&amp;3\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}x\y\z\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}3\1\7\end{pmatrix}$$</p>
<p><strong>We compute the determinant</strong> of the coefficient matrix:
$$D=\begin{vmatrix}1&amp;1&amp;1\1&amp;-1&amp;1\2&amp;1&amp;3\end{vmatrix}=1(-3-1)-1(3-2)+1(1+2)=(-4)-(1)+(3)=-2\neq0$$</p>
<p>Since $D\neq0$, the system has a <strong>unique solution</strong>. This corresponds to <strong>three planes meeting at a single point</strong>.</p>
<p>We solve by Cramer's rule or Gaussian elimination:
$$x=\frac{D_x}{D}=\frac{\begin{vmatrix}3&amp;1&amp;1\1&amp;-1&amp;1\7&amp;1&amp;3\end{vmatrix}}{-2}=\frac{3(-3-1)-1(3-7)+1(1+7)}{-2}=\frac{-12+4+8}{-2}=\frac{0}{-2}=0$$
$$y=\frac{D_y}{D}=\frac{\begin{vmatrix}1&amp;3&amp;1\1&amp;1&amp;1\2&amp;7&amp;3\end{vmatrix}}{-2}=\frac{1(3-7)-3(3-2)+1(7-2)}{-2}=\frac{-4-3+5}{-2}=\frac{-2}{-2}=1$$
$$z=3-x-y=3-0-1=2$$</p>
<p><strong>Intersection point:</strong> $P(0,1,2)$.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Study the position of the three planes $\pi_1:\;x+y=2$, $\pi_2:\;y+z=3$, $\pi_3:\;x+z=1$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> System:
$$\begin{cases}x+y=2\y+z=3\x+z=1\end{cases}$$
$D=\begin{vmatrix}1&amp;1&amp;0\0&amp;1&amp;1\1&amp;0&amp;1\end{vmatrix}=1(1-0)-1(0-1)+0=1+1=2\neq0$.
Unique solution. The three planes meet at a point.
Adding all three equations: $2x+2y+2z=6 \Rightarrow x+y+z=3$.
From $\pi_1$: $z=1$; from $\pi_2$: $x=0$; from $\pi_3$: $y=2$.
<strong>Intersection point: $(0,2,1)$</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Determine whether the planes $\pi_1:\;x+y+z=1$, $\pi_2:\;x+y+z=2$, $\pi_3:\;x+y+z=3$ have any common point.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> All three have the same normal vector $(1,1,1)$, they are mutually parallel (and distinct, since their constant terms are different). <strong>They have no common point</strong> (inconsistent system).</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Study the relative position of:
   $$\pi_1:\; x+2y-z=3 \quad \pi_2:\; 2x+4y-2z=6 \quad \pi_3:\; x-y+z=1$$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> We observe that $\pi_2=2\pi_1$: they are <strong>coincident</strong>. The system reduces to:
$$\begin{cases}x+2y-z=3\x-y+z=1\end{cases}$$
The planes $\pi_1$ (=$\pi_2$) and $\pi_3$ are intersecting (normals $(1,2,-1)$ and $(1,-1,1)$ are not proportional).
The system has infinitely many solutions (a line): <strong>the three planes share a line</strong> (the plane $\pi_2$ is the same as $\pi_1$, and the other two meet in a line).</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>For what value of $k$ do the three planes $\pi_1:\;x+y+z=2$, $\pi_2:\;x-y+kz=0$, $\pi_3:\;2x+ky+z=3$ have a unique solution?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The system has a unique solution $\Leftrightarrow$ $D\neq0$:
$$D=\begin{vmatrix}1&amp;1&amp;1\1&amp;-1&amp;k\2&amp;k&amp;1\end{vmatrix}=1(-1-k^2)-1(1-2k)+1(k+2)$$
$=-1-k^2-1+2k+k+2 = -k^2+3k$
$D\neq0 \Leftrightarrow -k^2+3k\neq0 \Leftrightarrow k(k-3)\neq0 \Leftrightarrow k\neq0$ and $k\neq3$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Consider the planes:
   $$\pi_1:\; x+y-z=2, \quad \pi_2:\; 2x-y+z=1, \quad \pi_3:\; x+ay+bz=c$$</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Study the relative position of $\pi_1$ and $\pi_2$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Find $a$, $b$, $c$ such that the system of three planes is inconsistent (no solution), with $\pi_3$ not parallel to $\pi_1$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $\vec{n}_1=(1,1,-1)$, $\vec{n}_2=(2,-1,1)$: not proportional. <strong>Intersecting.</strong>
Line of intersection: $\pi_1+\pi_2$: $3x=3 \Rightarrow x=1$. From $\pi_1$: $y-z=1$. Line: $(1, 1+t, t)$, $t\in\mathbb{R}$, or equivalently $(x,y,z)=(1,1,0)+t(0,1,1)$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> For the system to be inconsistent with $\pi_3$ not parallel to $\pi_1$: the line of intersection $\pi_1\cap\pi_2$ must be parallel to $\pi_3$ without being contained in it.
The line has direction vector $(0,1,1)$. For $\pi_3 \parallel$ to the line: $(0,1,1)\cdot(1,a,b)=0 \Rightarrow a+b=0 \Rightarrow b=-a$.
For the system to be inconsistent: the line does not belong to $\pi_3$: the point $(1,1,0)$ is not in $\pi_3$: $1+a\cdot1+b\cdot0\neq c \Rightarrow 1+a\neq c$.
Example: $a=1$, $b=-1$, $c=0$ (then $1+1=2\neq0$ ✓). Plane: $x+y-z=0$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>If the determinant of the coefficient matrix of a system of three planes is zero:</li>
<li>a) The three planes meet at a unique point</li>
<li>b) The system is always inconsistent</li>
<li>c) The system has infinitely many solutions or is inconsistent</li>
<li>d) The three planes are coincident</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) If $D=0$, the system is either compatible indeterminate (infinitely many solutions: a point, a line, or a plane) or inconsistent. A more detailed rank analysis is required.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Three planes that pairwise meet in mutually parallel (and distinct) lines form a configuration called:</li>
<li>a) A pencil of planes</li>
<li>b) A consistent determinate system</li>
<li>c) A prism (inconsistent system with parallel lines of intersection)</li>
<li>d) Coincident planes</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) This geometric configuration, where each pair of planes meets in a line and the three lines are parallel, corresponds to an inconsistent system whose configuration resembles a "triedral prism" or prismatic-pencil system. The corresponding system of equations has no solution.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<hr />
<h5>5.4.1 Angle between Two Lines</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Calculate the angle formed by the lines $r:\;\dfrac{x-1}{2}=\dfrac{y}{1}=\dfrac{z+1}{-2}$ and $s:\;\dfrac{x}{1}=\dfrac{y-3}{2}=\dfrac{z-1}{2}$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>The direction vectors are $\vec{d}_r=(2,1,-2)$ and $\vec{d}_s=(1,2,2)$.</p>
<p>The angle $\theta$ between two lines is calculated as:
$$\cos\theta = \frac{|\vec{d}_r\cdot\vec{d}_s|}{|\vec{d}_r||\vec{d}_s|}$$</p>
<p>(We take the absolute value because the angle between lines is the acute angle, $0\leq\theta\leq90°$.)</p>
<p>$$\vec{d}_r\cdot\vec{d}_s = 2\cdot1+1\cdot2+(-2)\cdot2 = 2+2-4=0$$</p>
<p>$$\cos\theta=\frac{|0|}{3\cdot3}=0 \Rightarrow \theta=90°$$</p>
<p><strong>The lines are perpendicular.</strong></p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Calculate the angle between the lines with direction vectors $\vec{d}_1=(1,0,1)$ and $\vec{d}_2=(0,1,1)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong>
$$\cos\theta=\frac{|\vec{d}_1\cdot\vec{d}_2|}{|\vec{d}_1||\vec{d}_2|}=\frac{|0+0+1|}{\sqrt{2}\cdot\sqrt{2}}=\frac{1}{2}$$
$$\theta=\arccos!\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)=60°$$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Determine whether the lines $r:\;(1,2,3)+\lambda(1,-1,2)$ and $s:\;(0,0,1)+\mu(3,1,-1)$ are perpendicular.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{d}_r=(1,-1,2)$, $\vec{d}_s=(3,1,-1)$.
$\vec{d}_r\cdot\vec{d}_s=3-1-2=0$. <strong>Yes, they are perpendicular.</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the angle between the lines:
   $$r:\;\begin{cases}x=t\y=2t\z=3t\end{cases} \qquad s:\;\begin{cases}x=1+2\mu\y=-1-\mu\z=3\mu\end{cases}$$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{d}_r=(1,2,3)$, $\vec{d}_s=(2,-1,3)$.
$$\cos\theta=\frac{|2-2+9|}{\sqrt{14}\cdot\sqrt{14}}=\frac{9}{14}$$
$$\theta=\arccos!\left(\frac{9}{14}\right)\approx 49{,}99°\approx50°$$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find $k$ such that the lines $r:\;\vec{d}_r=(k,1,2)$ and $s:\;\vec{d}_s=(1,k,-1)$ are perpendicular.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{d}_r\cdot\vec{d}_s=k\cdot1+1\cdot k+2\cdot(-1)=2k-2=0 \Rightarrow k=1$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Given the lines:
   $$r:\;\frac{x-2}{1}=\frac{y-1}{-1}=\frac{z}{2}, \qquad s:\;\frac{x}{2}=\frac{y+1}{1}=\frac{z-3}{-1}$$</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Find the angle formed by $r$ and $s$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Determine whether $r$ and $s$ are intersecting or skew; if intersecting, find the intersection point.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $\vec{d}_r=(1,-1,2)$, $\vec{d}_s=(2,1,-1)$.
$$\cos\theta=\frac{|2-1-2|}{\sqrt{6}\cdot\sqrt{6}}=\frac{1}{6}$$
$$\theta=\arccos!\left(\frac{1}{6}\right)\approx80{,}4°$$</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Parametric equations: $r$: $x=2+t, y=1-t, z=2t$; $s$: $x=2\mu, y=-1+\mu, z=3-\mu$.
System:
$$2+t=2\mu \quad(I)$$
$$1-t=-1+\mu \Rightarrow \mu=2-t \quad(II)$$
$$2t=3-\mu \quad(III)$$
From $(I)$ and $(II)$: $2+t=2(2-t)=4-2t \Rightarrow 3t=2 \Rightarrow t=2/3$, $\mu=4/3$.
We check in $(III)$: $2(2/3)=4/3$ and $3-4/3=5/3$. $4/3\neq5/3$. <strong>Inconsistent</strong>: $r$ and $s$ are <strong>skew</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The angle between two lines with direction vectors $\vec{d}_1$ and $\vec{d}_2$ is always calculated as:</li>
<li>a) $\arccos!\left(\dfrac{\vec{d}_1\cdot\vec{d}_2}{|\vec{d}_1||\vec{d}_2|}\right)$, which may be obtuse</li>
<li>b) $\arccos!\left(\dfrac{|\vec{d}_1\cdot\vec{d}_2|}{|\vec{d}_1||\vec{d}_2|}\right)$, always between $0°$ and $90°$</li>
<li>c) $\arcsin!\left(\dfrac{\vec{d}_1\cdot\vec{d}_2}{|\vec{d}_1||\vec{d}_2|}\right)$</li>
<li>d) $\arctan!\left(\dfrac{|\vec{d}_1\times\vec{d}_2|}{|\vec{d}_1||\vec{d}_2|}\right)$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) By convention, the angle between two lines is the acute (or right) angle they form, so the absolute value of the cosine is taken.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Two lines are perpendicular if and only if:</li>
<li>a) Their direction vectors are equal</li>
<li>b) Their direction vectors are proportional</li>
<li>c) The dot product of their direction vectors is zero</li>
<li>d) The modulus of the cross product of their direction vectors is zero</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) Perpendicularity is equivalent to $\vec{d}_1\cdot\vec{d}_2=0$, which implies the angle between them is $90°$.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.4.2 Angle between a Line and a Plane</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Calculate the angle formed by the line $r:\;x=1+2t,\;y=t,\;z=-1+t$ with the plane $\pi:\;x-y+2z=0$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>The angle $\varphi$ between a line (with direction vector $\vec{d}$) and a plane (with normal vector $\vec{n}$) is calculated as the complement of the angle between $\vec{d}$ and $\vec{n}$:</p>
<p>$$\sin\varphi = \frac{|\vec{d}\cdot\vec{n}|}{|\vec{d}||\vec{n}|}$$</p>
<p>With $\vec{d}=(2,1,1)$ and $\vec{n}=(1,-1,2)$:
$$\vec{d}\cdot\vec{n}=2-1+2=3$$
$$|\vec{d}|=\sqrt{4+1+1}=\sqrt{6}, \quad |\vec{n}|=\sqrt{1+1+4}=\sqrt{6}$$
$$\sin\varphi=\frac{|3|}{\sqrt{6}\cdot\sqrt{6}}=\frac{3}{6}=\frac{1}{2}$$
$$\boxed{\varphi=\arcsin!\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)=30°}$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Calculate the angle between the line $r:\;\vec{d}=(1,0,1)$ and the plane $\pi:\;\vec{n}=(1,1,0)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong>
$$\sin\varphi=\frac{|1\cdot1+0\cdot1+1\cdot0|}{\sqrt{2}\cdot\sqrt{2}}=\frac{1}{2}$$
$$\varphi=30°$$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>What condition must $\vec{d}$ and $\vec{n}$ satisfy for the line to be perpendicular to the plane?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The line is perpendicular to the plane when $\varphi=90°$, which occurs when $\sin\varphi=1$, i.e., when $\vec{d}\parallel\vec{n}$: the direction vector of the line is proportional to the normal vector of the plane. Equivalently, $\vec{d}\times\vec{n}=\vec{0}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the angle formed by the line $r:\;\dfrac{x-1}{3}=\dfrac{y+2}{-1}=\dfrac{z}{2}$ with the plane $\pi:\;2x+y-z=5$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{d}=(3,-1,2)$, $\vec{n}=(2,1,-1)$.
$$\sin\varphi=\frac{|6-1-2|}{\sqrt{14}\cdot\sqrt{6}}=\frac{3}{\sqrt{84}}=\frac{3}{2\sqrt{21}}=\frac{3\sqrt{21}}{42}=\frac{\sqrt{21}}{14}$$
$$\varphi=\arcsin!\left(\frac{\sqrt{21}}{14}\right)\approx \arcsin(0{,}327)\approx19{,}1°$$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>For what values of $m$ does the line $r:\;\vec{d}=(m,1,2)$ form an angle of $30°$ with the plane $x+y+z=0$?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{n}=(1,1,1)$, $\sin30°=1/2$.
$$\frac{|m+1+2|}{\sqrt{m^2+5}\cdot\sqrt{3}}=\frac{1}{2}$$
$$\frac{|m+3|}{\sqrt{3(m^2+5)}}=\frac{1}{2}$$
$2|m+3|=\sqrt{3(m^2+5)}$. Squaring: $4(m+3)^2=3m^2+15$.
$4m^2+24m+36=3m^2+15 \Rightarrow m^2+24m+21=0$
$$m=\frac{-24\pm\sqrt{576-84}}{2}=\frac{-24\pm\sqrt{492}}{2}=\frac{-24\pm2\sqrt{123}}{2}=-12\pm\sqrt{123}$$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Let the line $r:\;\dfrac{x}{1}=\dfrac{y-1}{2}=\dfrac{z+2}{-1}$ and the plane $\pi:\;ax-y+2z=3$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Find the angle between $r$ and $\pi$ when $a=2$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> For what value of $a$ is the line $r$ parallel to the plane $\pi$?</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> For what value of $a$ is the line $r$ perpendicular to the plane $\pi$?</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>$\vec{d}_r=(1,2,-1)$, $\vec{n}=(a,-1,2)$.</p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $a=2$: $\vec{n}=(2,-1,2)$.
$$\sin\varphi=\frac{|2-2-2|}{\sqrt{6}\cdot3}=\frac{2}{3\sqrt{6}}=\frac{2\sqrt{6}}{18}=\frac{\sqrt{6}}{9}$$
$$\varphi=\arcsin!\left(\frac{\sqrt{6}}{9}\right)\approx15{,}8°$$</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> $r\parallel\pi \Leftrightarrow \vec{d}\cdot\vec{n}=0$: $a-2-2=a-4=0 \Rightarrow a=4$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> $r\perp\pi \Leftrightarrow \vec{d}\parallel\vec{n}$: $(1,2,-1)=k(a,-1,2)$. $1=ka$, $2=-k$, $-1=2k$. From the second: $k=-1/2$. From the third: $k=-1/2$ ✓. From the first: $a=1/k=-2$. <strong>$a=-2$</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The angle between a line and a plane is calculated using:</li>
<li>a) The cosine of the angle between the direction vector and the normal vector</li>
<li>b) The sine of the angle between the direction vector and the normal vector</li>
<li>c) The cosine of the angle between the direction vector and a vector in the plane</li>
<li>d) The arctangent of the distance between the line and the plane</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) $\sin\varphi = \dfrac{|\vec{d}\cdot\vec{n}|}{|\vec{d}||\vec{n}|}$. The angle between the line and the plane is the complement of the angle between the line and the normal, which leads to the sine.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If $\vec{d}\cdot\vec{n}=0$, the line with direction vector $\vec{d}$ and the plane with normal vector $\vec{n}$:</li>
<li>a) Are perpendicular</li>
<li>b) Are parallel (the line is parallel to the plane or contained in it)</li>
<li>c) Meet at an angle of $45°$</li>
<li>d) Meet at a point</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) $\vec{d}\cdot\vec{n}=0$ implies that the line is parallel to the plane or contained in it (the angle between the line and the plane is $0°$).</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.4.3 Angle between Two Planes (Dihedral Angle)</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Calculate the dihedral angle between the planes $\pi_1:\; 2x-y+z=3$ and $\pi_2:\; x+y-z=1$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>The angle $\theta$ between two planes is the angle between their normal vectors (taking the acute angle):</p>
<p>$$\cos\theta = \frac{|\vec{n}_1\cdot\vec{n}_2|}{|\vec{n}_1||\vec{n}_2|}$$</p>
<p>With $\vec{n}_1=(2,-1,1)$ and $\vec{n}_2=(1,1,-1)$:
$$\vec{n}_1\cdot\vec{n}_2 = 2-1-1=0$$</p>
<p>$$\cos\theta=0 \Rightarrow \theta=90°$$</p>
<p><strong>The planes are perpendicular.</strong></p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Calculate the angle between the planes $\pi_1:\;x+y=0$ and $\pi_2:\;y+z=0$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{n}_1=(1,1,0)$, $\vec{n}_2=(0,1,1)$.
$$\cos\theta=\frac{|0+1+0|}{\sqrt{2}\cdot\sqrt{2}}=\frac{1}{2}$$
$$\theta=60°$$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>When are two planes perpendicular? State the condition in terms of their normal vectors.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Two planes are perpendicular when the dihedral angle between them is $90°$, i.e., when $\cos\theta=0$, which is equivalent to their normal vectors being perpendicular: $\vec{n}_1\cdot\vec{n}_2=0$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the angle formed by the planes $\pi_1:\;2x+y-2z=3$ and $\pi_2:\;3x+6z=1$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{n}_1=(2,1,-2)$, $\vec{n}_2=(3,0,6)$.
$$\cos\theta=\frac{|6+0-12|}{3\cdot\sqrt{45}}=\frac{6}{3\cdot3\sqrt{5}}=\frac{6}{9\sqrt{5}}=\frac{2}{3\sqrt{5}}=\frac{2\sqrt{5}}{15}$$
$$\theta=\arccos!\left(\frac{2\sqrt{5}}{15}\right)\approx\arccos(0{,}298)\approx72{,}7°$$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find $k$ such that the planes $\pi_1:\;kx+2y-z=0$ and $\pi_2:\;x+ky+2z=3$ are perpendicular.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{n}_1\cdot\vec{n}_2=0$: $k\cdot1+2\cdot k+(-1)\cdot2=3k-2=0 \Rightarrow k=\dfrac{2}{3}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Let the planes $\pi:\;x-y+2z=4$ and $\sigma:\;2x+y+az=1$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Find $a$ such that $\pi$ and $\sigma$ are perpendicular.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> With the value of $a$ found, determine the line of intersection of $\pi$ and $\sigma$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Calculate the angle between $\pi$ and the coordinate plane $XOY$ (equation $z=0$).</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $\vec{n}<em>\pi=(1,-1,2)$, $\vec{n}</em>\sigma=(2,1,a)$. $\vec{n}<em>\pi\cdot\vec{n}</em>\sigma=0$: $2-1+2a=0 \Rightarrow 2a=-1 \Rightarrow a=-\dfrac{1}{2}$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> With $a=-1/2$: system $x-y+2z=4$ and $2x+y-z/2=1$ (mult. by 2: $4x+2y-z=2$).
$\pi+\sigma$: $(x-y+2z)+(2x+y-z/2)=5 \Rightarrow 3x+3z/2=5$, i.e. $6x+3z=10$.
Parametrising: $z=t$, $x=(10-3t)/6$. From $\pi$: $y=x+2z-4=(10-3t)/6+2t-4=\dfrac{10-3t+12t-24}{6}=\dfrac{9t-14}{6}$.
Line: point (with $t=0$): $(5/3,-7/3,0)$, direction vector proportional to $(-3,9,6)/6=(-1,3,2)$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> The plane $XOY$ has $\vec{n}_{XOY}=(0,0,1)$.
$$\cos\theta=\frac{|(1)(0)+(-1)(0)+(2)(1)|}{\sqrt{6}\cdot1}=\frac{2}{\sqrt{6}}=\frac{2\sqrt{6}}{6}=\frac{\sqrt{6}}{3}$$
$$\theta=\arccos!\left(\frac{\sqrt{6}}{3}\right)\approx35{,}3°$$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The angle between the planes $x=0$ ($YOZ$ plane) and $y=0$ ($XOZ$ plane) is:</li>
<li>a) $0°$</li>
<li>b) $45°$</li>
<li>c) $60°$</li>
<li>d) $90°$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> d) The normals are $\vec{n}_1=(1,0,0)$ and $\vec{n}_2=(0,1,0)$: $\vec{n}_1\cdot\vec{n}_2=0$, so the angle is $90°$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If the angle between two planes is $\theta$, the supplementary angle $180°-\theta$ is also a possible "dihedral angle". Why is the acute angle taken?</li>
<li>a) Because the obtuse angle does not exist between planes</li>
<li>b) Because the dihedral angle is by convention always taken as the smaller of the two</li>
<li>c) Because the absolute value in the formula guarantees the result is the acute angle</li>
<li>d) Both b) and c) are correct</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> d) The angle between two planes is defined as the smaller of the two dihedral angles formed (between $0°$ and $90°$), and the formula $\cos\theta=\dfrac{|\vec{n}_1\cdot\vec{n}_2|}{|\vec{n}_1||\vec{n}_2|}$ automatically guarantees this result thanks to the absolute value.</p>
</blockquote>
