<h5>5.5.1 Distance between Two Points</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Calculate the distance between the points $A(1,-2,3)$ and $B(4,2,-1)$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>The distance between two points in $\mathbb{R}^3$ is:
$$d(A,B) = |\overrightarrow{AB}| = \sqrt{(x_B-x_A)^2+(y_B-y_A)^2+(z_B-z_A)^2}$$</p>
<p>$$d(A,B) = \sqrt{(4-1)^2+(2-(-2))^2+(-1-3)^2} = \sqrt{9+16+16} = \sqrt{41}$$</p>
<p>$$\boxed{d(A,B)=\sqrt{41}\approx6{,}40}$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Calculate the distance between $P(-1,0,2)$ and $Q(3,4,-2)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong>
$$d=\sqrt{(3+1)^2+(4-0)^2+(-2-2)^2}=\sqrt{16+16+16}=\sqrt{48}=4\sqrt{3}$$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The midpoint of segment $AB$ has coordinates $M(2,-1,3)$ and $A(0,1,-1)$. Find $B$ and $d(A,B)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $M=\dfrac{A+B}{2} \Rightarrow B=2M-A=(4,-3,7)$.
$d(A,B)=\sqrt{16+16+64}=\sqrt{96}=4\sqrt{6}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the points on the line $r:\;x=1+t,\;y=2-t,\;z=t$ equidistant from $A(0,0,0)$ and $B(6,0,6)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Let $P(1+t,2-t,t)\in r$.
$d(P,A)^2=(1+t)^2+(2-t)^2+t^2=1+2t+t^2+4-4t+t^2+t^2=3t^2-2t+5$
$d(P,B)^2=(1+t-6)^2+(2-t)^2+(t-6)^2=(t-5)^2+(2-t)^2+(t-6)^2$
$=t^2-10t+25+4-4t+t^2+t^2-12t+36=3t^2-26t+65$
Equating: $3t^2-2t+5=3t^2-26t+65 \Rightarrow 24t=60 \Rightarrow t=5/2$.
Point: $P(7/2,-1/2,5/2)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find the point on the line $r:\;\dfrac{x}{1}=\dfrac{y-1}{1}=\dfrac{z}{2}$ closest to the origin.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Generic point: $P(t,1+t,2t)$.
$d(P,O)^2=t^2+(1+t)^2+4t^2=t^2+1+2t+t^2+4t^2=6t^2+2t+1$.
Minimum: $\dfrac{d}{dt}(6t^2+2t+1)=12t+2=0 \Rightarrow t=-\dfrac{1}{6}$.
Closest point: $P!\left(-\dfrac{1}{6}, \dfrac{5}{6}, -\dfrac{1}{3}\right)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Given the points $A(1,0,-1)$, $B(3,2,1)$ and $C(2,-1,3)$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Calculate the perimeter of triangle $ABC$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Find the midpoint of $AC$ and the length of the median from $B$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong>
$d(A,B)=\sqrt{4+4+4}=\sqrt{12}=2\sqrt{3}$
$d(B,C)=\sqrt{1+9+4}=\sqrt{14}$
$d(A,C)=\sqrt{1+1+16}=\sqrt{18}=3\sqrt{2}$
Perimeter $= 2\sqrt{3}+\sqrt{14}+3\sqrt{2}\approx3{,}46+3{,}74+4{,}24\approx11{,}44$ units.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Midpoint of $AC$: $M_{AC}=\left(\dfrac{3}{2},-\dfrac{1}{2},1\right)$.
Median from $B$: $d(B,M_{AC})=\sqrt{(3-3/2)^2+(2+1/2)^2+(1-1)^2}=\sqrt{9/4+25/4}=\sqrt{34/4}=\dfrac{\sqrt{34}}{2}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The distance between $A(a,b,c)$ and the origin $O(0,0,0)$ is:</li>
<li>a) $a+b+c$</li>
<li>b) $|a|+|b|+|c|$</li>
<li>c) $\sqrt{a+b+c}$</li>
<li>d) $\sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> d) It is the modulus of the position vector: $|\overrightarrow{OA}|=\sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If $d(A,B)=0$, then:</li>
<li>a) $A$ and $B$ are the same point</li>
<li>b) $A$ and $B$ lie in the same coordinate plane</li>
<li>c) $A$ and $B$ are symmetrically opposite with respect to the origin</li>
<li>d) The vector $\overrightarrow{AB}$ is a unit vector</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> a) $d(A,B)=0 \Leftrightarrow |\overrightarrow{AB}|=0 \Leftrightarrow \overrightarrow{AB}=\vec{0} \Leftrightarrow A=B$.</p>
</blockquote>
