<h5>5.5.2 Distance from a Point to a Line</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Calculate the distance from the point $P(2,3,1)$ to the line $r:\;(x,y,z)=(1,0,2)+\lambda(1,-1,1)$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Method using the cross product:</strong></p>
<p>Let $A(1,0,2)$ be a point on $r$ and $\vec{d}=(1,-1,1)$ the direction vector.</p>
<p>$$\overrightarrow{AP} = P - A = (1,3,-1)$$</p>
<p>$$\overrightarrow{AP}\times\vec{d} = \begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\1&amp;3&amp;-1\1&amp;-1&amp;1\end{vmatrix} = (3\cdot1-(-1)(-1))\vec{i}-(1\cdot1-(-1)\cdot1)\vec{j}+(1\cdot(-1)-3\cdot1)\vec{k}$$
$$= (3-1)\vec{i}-(1+1)\vec{j}+(-1-3)\vec{k} = (2,-2,-4)$$</p>
<p>$$|\overrightarrow{AP}\times\vec{d}| = \sqrt{4+4+16}=\sqrt{24}=2\sqrt{6}$$
$$|\vec{d}|=\sqrt{1+1+1}=\sqrt{3}$$</p>
<p>$$\boxed{d(P,r)=\frac{|\overrightarrow{AP}\times\vec{d}|}{|\vec{d}|}=\frac{2\sqrt{6}}{\sqrt{3}}=2\sqrt{2}}$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Calculate the distance from the point $Q(0,0,0)$ to the line $r:\;(x,y,z)=(1,1,1)+\lambda(1,0,0)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $A=(1,1,1)$, $\vec{d}=(1,0,0)$, $\overrightarrow{AQ}=(-1,-1,-1)$.
$\overrightarrow{AQ}\times\vec{d}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\-1&amp;-1&amp;-1\1&amp;0&amp;0\end{vmatrix}=(0-0)\vec{i}-(0+1)\vec{j}+(0+1)\vec{k}=(0,-1,1)$.
$d=\dfrac{|(0,-1,1)|}{1}=\sqrt{2}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>When is the distance from a point to a line zero? Give a geometric interpretation.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The distance is zero when $\overrightarrow{AP}\times\vec{d}=\vec{0}$, i.e., when $\overrightarrow{AP}$ and $\vec{d}$ are proportional, which means $P$ is a point on the line $r$. Geometrically: $P\in r$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Calculate the distance from the point $A(1,-1,2)$ to the line $r:\;\dfrac{x}{2}=\dfrac{y+1}{1}=\dfrac{z-2}{-1}$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Point on $r$: $B(0,-1,2)$. $\vec{d}=(2,1,-1)$.
$\overrightarrow{BA}=(1,0,0)$.
$\overrightarrow{BA}\times\vec{d}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\1&amp;0&amp;0\2&amp;1&amp;-1\end{vmatrix}=(0-0)\vec{i}-((-1)-0)\vec{j}+(1-0)\vec{k}=(0,1,1)$.
$d=\dfrac{\sqrt{0+1+1}}{\sqrt{4+1+1}}=\dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{6}}=\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{3}}=\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{3}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find the distance from the point $P(2,0,-1)$ to the line passing through $A(1,1,1)$ and $B(3,-1,0)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{d}=\overrightarrow{AB}=(2,-2,-1)$. $\overrightarrow{AP}=(1,-1,-2)$.
$\overrightarrow{AP}\times\vec{d}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\1&amp;-1&amp;-2\2&amp;-2&amp;-1\end{vmatrix}=(1-4)\vec{i}-(-1+4)\vec{j}+(-2+2)\vec{k}=(-3,-3,0)$.
$|\overrightarrow{AP}\times\vec{d}|=\sqrt{9+9}=3\sqrt{2}$.
$|\vec{d}|=\sqrt{4+4+1}=3$.
$d=\dfrac{3\sqrt{2}}{3}=\sqrt{2}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Let the line $r:\;\begin{cases}x=1+t\y=2-2t\z=t\end{cases}$ and the point $P(3,0,4)$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Calculate the distance from $P$ to $r$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Find the foot of the perpendicular from $P$ to $r$ (the point on $r$ closest to $P$).</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $A=(1,2,0)$, $\vec{d}=(1,-2,1)$, $\overrightarrow{AP}=(2,-2,4)$.
$\overrightarrow{AP}\times\vec{d}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\2&amp;-2&amp;4\1&amp;-2&amp;1\end{vmatrix}=(-2+8)\vec{i}-(2-4)\vec{j}+(-4+2)\vec{k}=(6,2,-2)$.
$|\overrightarrow{AP}\times\vec{d}|=\sqrt{36+4+4}=\sqrt{44}=2\sqrt{11}$.
$|\vec{d}|=\sqrt{6}$.
$$d(P,r)=\frac{2\sqrt{11}}{\sqrt{6}}=2\sqrt{\frac{11}{6}}=\frac{2\sqrt{66}}{6}=\frac{\sqrt{66}}{3}$$</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> The foot of the perpendicular $H$ is the point on $r$ such that $\overrightarrow{HP}\perp\vec{d}$:
$H=(1+t, 2-2t, t)$. $\overrightarrow{HP}=(2-t, -2+2t, 4-t)$.
$\overrightarrow{HP}\cdot\vec{d}=(2-t)-(- 4+4t)+(4-t)=2-t+4-4t+4-t=10-6t=0 \Rightarrow t=5/3$.
$H=\left(\dfrac{8}{3}, -\dfrac{4}{3}, \dfrac{5}{3}\right)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The formula for the distance from a point $P$ to a line $r$ (with point $A$ and direction vector $\vec{d}$) is:</li>
<li>a) $\dfrac{\overrightarrow{AP}\cdot\vec{d}}{|\vec{d}|}$</li>
<li>b) $\dfrac{|\overrightarrow{AP}\times\vec{d}|}{|\vec{d}|}$</li>
<li>c) $\dfrac{|\overrightarrow{AP}\cdot\vec{d}|}{|\vec{d}|}$</li>
<li>d) $|\overrightarrow{AP}|\cdot|\vec{d}|$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) The distance is $\dfrac{|\overrightarrow{AP}\times\vec{d}|}{|\vec{d}|}$, using the modulus of the cross product.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The foot of the perpendicular from $P$ to the line $r$ is the point $H\in r$ such that:</li>
<li>a) $\overrightarrow{HP}$ is parallel to $\vec{d}$</li>
<li>b) $\overrightarrow{HP}$ is perpendicular to $\vec{d}$, i.e. $\overrightarrow{HP}\cdot\vec{d}=0$</li>
<li>c) $|HP|$ is maximum</li>
<li>d) $H$ is on the plane perpendicular to $r$ passing through the origin</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) $H$ is the foot of the perpendicular, so $\overrightarrow{HP}\perp\vec{d}$, which translates to $\overrightarrow{HP}\cdot\vec{d}=0$.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.5.3 Distance from a Point to a Plane</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Calculate the distance from the point $P(1,2,-1)$ to the plane $\pi:\; 2x - y + 2z + 3 = 0$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>The formula for the distance from a point $(x_0,y_0,z_0)$ to the plane $ax+by+cz+d=0$ is:</p>
<p>$$d(P,\pi) = \frac{|ax_0+by_0+cz_0+d|}{\sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}}$$</p>
<p>With $P(1,2,-1)$, $a=2$, $b=-1$, $c=2$, $d=3$:</p>
<p>$$d(P,\pi)=\frac{|2(1)+(-1)(2)+2(-1)+3|}{\sqrt{4+1+4}}=\frac{|2-2-2+3|}{\sqrt{9}}=\frac{|1|}{3}=\frac{1}{3}$$</p>
<p>$$\boxed{d(P,\pi)=\frac{1}{3}}$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Calculate the distance from the origin $O(0,0,0)$ to the plane $\pi:\;3x-4y+0z=10$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong>
$$d(O,\pi)=\frac{|3\cdot0-4\cdot0-10|}{\sqrt{9+16}}=\frac{10}{5}=2$$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>How far is the point $A(2,-1,3)$ from the plane $\pi:\;x+2y-2z=6$?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong>
$$d=\frac{|2+2(-1)-2(3)-6|}{\sqrt{1+4+4}}=\frac{|2-2-6-6|}{3}=\frac{12}{3}=4$$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the point on the plane $\pi:\;x+y+z=1$ closest to the point $P(2,3,4)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The closest point $H$ lies on the line through $P$ with direction $\vec{n}=(1,1,1)$ (perpendicular to the plane).
Parametric equations: $(2+t, 3+t, 4+t)$. Substituting into $\pi$: $(2+t)+(3+t)+(4+t)=1 \Rightarrow 9+3t=1 \Rightarrow t=-8/3$.
$H=\left(2-\dfrac{8}{3}, 3-\dfrac{8}{3}, 4-\dfrac{8}{3}\right)=\left(-\dfrac{2}{3}, \dfrac{1}{3}, \dfrac{4}{3}\right)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Determine whether the points $A(1,0,2)$ and $B(-1,2,0)$ are on the same side of the plane $\pi:\;x-y+z=3$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Substituting into $x-y+z-3$:
$A$: $1-0+2-3=0$. $A$ <strong>belongs</strong> to the plane.
$B$: $-1-2+0-3=-6&lt;0$. $B$ is on the negative side of the plane.
One cannot speak of "same side" since $A\in\pi$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Let the point $P(2,-1,3)$ and the plane $\pi:\;x+2y-2z+k=0$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Calculate the distance from $P$ to $\pi$ as a function of $k$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Find $k$ such that $d(P,\pi)=2$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Find the orthogonal projection of $P$ onto $\pi$ for $k=1$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $\vec{n}=(1,2,-2)$, $|\vec{n}|=\sqrt{1+4+4}=3$.
$$d(P,\pi)=\frac{|2+2(-1)-2(3)+k|}{3}=\frac{|2-2-6+k|}{3}=\frac{|k-6|}{3}$$</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> $\dfrac{|k-6|}{3}=2 \Rightarrow |k-6|=6 \Rightarrow k=12$ or $k=0$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> With $k=1$: $d=|1-6|/3=5/3$. The projection $H$ of $P$ onto $\pi$ is found via the line through $P$ perpendicular to $\pi$: $(x,y,z)=(2,-1,3)+t(1,2,-2)$.
In $\pi$: $(2+t)+2(-1+2t)-2(3-2t)+1=0 \Rightarrow 2+t-2+4t-6+4t+1=0 \Rightarrow 9t-5=0 \Rightarrow t=5/9$.
$H=\left(\dfrac{23}{9}, \dfrac{1}{9}, \dfrac{17}{9}\right)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The distance from the point $(a,b,c)$ to the plane $x=0$ ($YOZ$ plane) is:</li>
<li>a) $\sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}$</li>
<li>b) $|a|$</li>
<li>c) $\sqrt{b^2+c^2}$</li>
<li>d) $a$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) The equation of the $YOZ$ plane is $x=0$ (or $x+0y+0z=0$). The distance is $\dfrac{|a\cdot1+b\cdot0+c\cdot0|}{\sqrt{1}}=|a|$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>To calculate the distance from a point to a plane using the analytical formula, the denominator is:</li>
<li>a) The modulus of the normal vector to the plane</li>
<li>b) The modulus of the position vector of the point</li>
<li>c) The constant term of the plane equation</li>
<li>d) The dot product of the point with the normal</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> a) In the formula $d=\dfrac{|ax_0+by_0+cz_0+d|}{\sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}}$, the denominator $\sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}=|\vec{n}|$ is the modulus of the normal vector to the plane.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.5.4 Distance between Two Parallel Lines</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Calculate the distance between the parallel lines:
$$r:\;\frac{x-1}{2}=\frac{y}{-1}=\frac{z+2}{1} \qquad s:\;\frac{x+3}{2}=\frac{y-1}{-1}=\frac{z}{1}$$</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>We verify parallelism: both have $\vec{d}=(2,-1,1)$: <strong>they are parallel</strong> (taking the point $(-3,1,0)$ of $s$ in $r$: $(-3-1)/2=-2$, $1/(-1)=-1\neq-2$: not coincident).</p>
<p><strong>Method:</strong> We take $A(1,0,-2)\in r$ and $B(-3,1,0)\in s$.
$$\overrightarrow{AB}=(-4,1,2)$$</p>
<p>The distance is the modulus of the component of $\overrightarrow{AB}$ perpendicular to $\vec{d}$:
$$d(r,s)=\frac{|\overrightarrow{AB}\times\vec{d}|}{|\vec{d}|}$$</p>
<p>$$\overrightarrow{AB}\times\vec{d}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\-4&amp;1&amp;2\2&amp;-1&amp;1\end{vmatrix}=(1+2)\vec{i}-(-4-4)\vec{j}+(4-2)\vec{k}=(3,8,2)$$</p>
<p>$$d=\frac{\sqrt{9+64+4}}{\sqrt{4+1+1}}=\frac{\sqrt{77}}{\sqrt{6}}=\sqrt{\frac{77}{6}}=\frac{\sqrt{462}}{6}$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Calculate the distance between $r:\;(x,y,z)=(0,1,0)+\lambda(1,1,0)$ and $s:\;(x,y,z)=(1,0,3)+\mu(2,2,0)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{d}_r=(1,1,0)$, $\vec{d}_s=(2,2,0)=2\vec{d}_r$: parallel.
$A=(0,1,0)\in r$, $B=(1,0,3)\in s$. $\overrightarrow{AB}=(1,-1,3)$.
$\overrightarrow{AB}\times\vec{d}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\1&amp;-1&amp;3\1&amp;1&amp;0\end{vmatrix}=(0-3)\vec{i}-(0-3)\vec{j}+(1+1)\vec{k}=(-3,3,2)$.
$d=\dfrac{\sqrt{9+9+4}}{\sqrt{2}}=\dfrac{\sqrt{22}}{\sqrt{2}}=\sqrt{11}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Why can we not calculate the distance between two parallel lines simply as the distance between their base points?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The distance between base points may not be the minimum distance between the lines. The distance between two parallel lines is the minimum of all distances between a point on $r$ and a point on $s$, which is the length of the segment perpendicular to both lines. The base point is any point, not necessarily the closest one.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Are the lines $r:\;(1,0,2)+\lambda(1,2,1)$ and $s:\;(3,4,5)+\mu(2,4,2)$ parallel? If so, calculate their distance.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{d}_r=(1,2,1)$, $\vec{d}_s=(2,4,2)=2\vec{d}_r$: proportional, they are parallel.
Point of $s$ in $r$?: $\overrightarrow{AB}=(2,4,3)$ with $A=(1,0,2)$, $B=(3,4,5)$.
$\overrightarrow{AB}\times\vec{d}_r=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\2&amp;4&amp;3\1&amp;2&amp;1\end{vmatrix}=(4-6)\vec{i}-(2-3)\vec{j}+(4-4)\vec{k}=(-2,1,0)$.
$d=\dfrac{\sqrt{4+1}}{|\vec{d}_r|}=\dfrac{\sqrt{5}}{\sqrt{6}}=\sqrt{\dfrac{5}{6}}=\dfrac{\sqrt{30}}{6}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Write two distinct parallel lines exactly $\sqrt{2}$ apart, with direction vector $(1,0,1)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> We take the line $r:\;x=t,y=0,z=t$ (through the origin with $\vec{d}=(1,0,1)$) and look for $s$ at distance $\sqrt{2}$.
A displacement perpendicular to $\vec{d}=(1,0,1)$: the vector $(0,1,0)$ is perpendicular to $\vec{d}$ and has modulus $1$. Displacing $\sqrt{2}$ in that direction: $s:\;x=t, y=\sqrt{2}, z=t$.
Verification: $A=(0,0,0)\in r$, $B=(0,\sqrt{2},0)\in s$. $\overrightarrow{AB}=(0,\sqrt{2},0)$.
$\overrightarrow{AB}\times\vec{d}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\0&amp;\sqrt{2}&amp;0\1&amp;0&amp;1\end{vmatrix}=(\sqrt{2})\vec{i}-(0)\vec{j}+(-\sqrt{2})\vec{k}=(\sqrt{2},0,-\sqrt{2})$.
$d=\dfrac{\sqrt{2+2}}{\sqrt{2}}=\dfrac{2}{\sqrt{2}}=\sqrt{2}$ ✓.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The lines $r:\;\dfrac{x-1}{2}=\dfrac{y+1}{-1}=\dfrac{z-2}{1}$ and $s:\;\dfrac{x+1}{4}=\dfrac{y-3}{-2}=\dfrac{z+1}{2}$ are parallel.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Verify that they are parallel and distinct.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Calculate the distance between them.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $\vec{d}_r=(2,-1,1)$, $\vec{d}_s=(4,-2,2)=2\vec{d}_r$ ✓ (parallel).
Point of $s$: $Q(-1,3,-1)$. In $r$: $(-1-1)/2=-1$; $(-1+1)/(-1)=0/(-1)=0\neq-1$. Does not belong: <strong>distinct</strong> ✓.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> $A(1,-1,2)\in r$, $B(-1,3,-1)\in s$. $\overrightarrow{AB}=(-2,4,-3)$.
$\overrightarrow{AB}\times\vec{d}_r=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\-2&amp;4&amp;-3\2&amp;-1&amp;1\end{vmatrix}=(4-3)\vec{i}-(-2+6)\vec{j}+(2-8)\vec{k}=(1,-4,-6)$.
$d=\dfrac{\sqrt{1+16+36}}{\sqrt{4+1+1}}=\dfrac{\sqrt{53}}{\sqrt{6}}=\sqrt{\dfrac{53}{6}}=\dfrac{\sqrt{318}}{6}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The distance between two parallel lines $r$ and $s$ is:</li>
<li>a) The distance between their direction vectors</li>
<li>b) The minimum distance between a point on $r$ and a point on $s$</li>
<li>c) The distance between their base points</li>
<li>d) Always infinite if they are parallel</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) It is the minimum possible distance between a point on $r$ and any point on $s$, which equals the length of the segment perpendicular to both.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>To calculate the distance between two parallel lines, the formula used is:</li>
<li>a) $d=|\overrightarrow{AB}|$</li>
<li>b) $d=\dfrac{|\overrightarrow{AB}\cdot\vec{d}|}{|\vec{d}|}$</li>
<li>c) $d=\dfrac{|\overrightarrow{AB}\times\vec{d}|}{|\vec{d}|}$</li>
<li>d) $d=\dfrac{\overrightarrow{AB}\cdot\vec{n}}{|\vec{n}|}$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) The same formula as for the distance from a point to a line, where $A\in r$ and $B\in s$.</p>
</blockquote>
