<h5>5.5.5 Distance between Two Skew Lines</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Calculate the distance between the skew lines:
$$r:\;(x,y,z)=(1,0,0)+\lambda(1,1,0) \qquad s:\;(x,y,z)=(0,0,1)+\mu(0,1,1)$$</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>The minimum distance between two skew lines is:
$$d(r,s) = \frac{|\overrightarrow{AB}\cdot(\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s)|}{|\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s|}$$</p>
<p>where $A\in r$, $B\in s$.</p>
<p><strong>Step 1:</strong> $A=(1,0,0)$, $B=(0,0,1)$, $\vec{d}_r=(1,1,0)$, $\vec{d}_s=(0,1,1)$.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2:</strong> $\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\1&amp;1&amp;0\0&amp;1&amp;1\end{vmatrix}=(1-0)\vec{i}-(1-0)\vec{j}+(1-0)\vec{k}=(1,-1,1)$.</p>
<p>$$|\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s|=\sqrt{3}$$</p>
<p><strong>Step 3:</strong> $\overrightarrow{AB}=B-A=(-1,0,1)$.</p>
<p>$$\overrightarrow{AB}\cdot(\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s)=(-1)(1)+(0)(-1)+(1)(1)=-1+0+1=0$$</p>
<p>$$d(r,s)=\frac{|0|}{\sqrt{3}}=0$$</p>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> $d=0$ implies the lines intersect. We verify whether they are actually skew: system $1+\lambda=0\mu, \lambda=\mu, 0=1+\mu$... From the third: $\mu=-1$, $\lambda=-1$; first: $1-1=0$ ✓. The lines are <strong>intersecting</strong> (not skew). The problem was incorrectly stated; another example follows:</p>
<p><strong>Correct example:</strong> $r:\;x=t,y=0,z=0$ and $s:\;x=0,y=1+\mu,z=\mu$.</p>
<p>$\vec{d}_r=(1,0,0)$, $\vec{d}_s=(0,1,1)$, $A=(0,0,0)$, $B=(0,1,0)$.</p>
<p>$\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s=(0\cdot1-0\cdot1)\vec{i}-(1\cdot1-0\cdot0)\vec{j}+(1\cdot1-0\cdot0)\vec{k}=(0,-1,1)$.</p>
<p>$\overrightarrow{AB}=(0,1,0)$.</p>
<p>$\overrightarrow{AB}\cdot(0,-1,1)=0-1+0=-1$.</p>
<p>$$d=\frac{|-1|}{\sqrt{2}}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}=\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Explain the difference between the distance between skew lines and the distance between parallel lines.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> In both cases the minimum distance is calculated using the same idea (the component perpendicular to both lines of the vector joining a point on each), but the formula differs:
- <strong>Parallel:</strong> $d=\dfrac{|\overrightarrow{AB}\times\vec{d}|}{|\vec{d}|}$ (both direction vectors are the same $\vec{d}$).
- <strong>Skew:</strong> $d=\dfrac{|\overrightarrow{AB}\cdot(\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s)|}{|\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s|}$ (the direction perpendicular to both is $\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s$).</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>What happens if $\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s=\vec{0}$ when trying to calculate the distance between two skew lines?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> If $\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s=\vec{0}$, the direction vectors are proportional, so the lines are parallel (or coincident), not skew. The skew-lines formula is not applicable; the parallel-lines formula must be used instead.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Calculate the distance between the skew lines:
   $$r:\;\frac{x}{1}=\frac{y-1}{0}=\frac{z}{0} \qquad s:\;\frac{x-1}{0}=\frac{y}{1}=\frac{z-1}{0}$$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{d}_r=(1,0,0)$, $\vec{d}_s=(0,1,0)$. Point $A=(0,1,0)\in r$ (with $y=1,z=0$ fixed), $B=(1,0,1)\in s$.
$\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\1&amp;0&amp;0\0&amp;1&amp;0\end{vmatrix}=(0)\vec{i}-(0)\vec{j}+(1)\vec{k}=(0,0,1)$. $|\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s|=1$.
$\overrightarrow{AB}=(1,-1,1)$.
$\overrightarrow{AB}\cdot(0,0,1)=1$.
$d=\dfrac{1}{1}=1$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Calculate the minimum distance between the lines:
   $$r:\;\begin{cases}x=2+t\y=1-t\z=3+2t\end{cases} \qquad s:\;\begin{cases}x=1+\mu\y=2+\mu\z=-1+\mu\end{cases}$$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{d}_r=(1,-1,2)$, $\vec{d}_s=(1,1,1)$.
$\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\1&amp;-1&amp;2\1&amp;1&amp;1\end{vmatrix}=(-1-2)\vec{i}-(1-2)\vec{j}+(1+1)\vec{k}=(-3,1,2)$. $|\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s|=\sqrt{14}$.
$A=(2,1,3)\in r$, $B=(1,2,-1)\in s$. $\overrightarrow{AB}=(-1,1,-4)$.
$\overrightarrow{AB}\cdot(-3,1,2)=3+1-8=-4$.
$d=\dfrac{4}{\sqrt{14}}=\dfrac{4\sqrt{14}}{14}=\dfrac{2\sqrt{14}}{7}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Given the lines:
   $$r:\;\frac{x-2}{1}=\frac{y}{2}=\frac{z+1}{-1} \qquad s:\;\frac{x}{2}=\frac{y-3}{-1}=\frac{z-2}{1}$$</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Verify that $r$ and $s$ are skew.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Calculate the minimum distance between $r$ and $s$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $\vec{d}_r=(1,2,-1)$, $\vec{d}_s=(2,-1,1)$: not proportional.
System: $2+t=2\mu$, $2t=-1+(-\mu)$... checking with full parametric equations:
$2+t=2\mu\;(I)$, $2t=3-\mu\;(II)$, $-1-t=2+\mu\;(III)$.
From $(III)$: $\mu=-3-t$. In $(I)$: $2+t=2(-3-t)=-6-2t \Rightarrow 3t=-8 \Rightarrow t=-8/3$, $\mu=-3+8/3=-1/3$.
We check in $(II)$: $2(-8/3)=-16/3$ and $3-(-1/3)=10/3$. $-16/3\neq10/3$: <strong>inconsistent</strong>. $r$ and $s$ are <strong>skew</strong> ✓.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> $\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\1&amp;2&amp;-1\2&amp;-1&amp;1\end{vmatrix}=(2-1)\vec{i}-(1+2)\vec{j}+(-1-4)\vec{k}=(1,-3,-5)$.
$|\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s|=\sqrt{1+9+25}=\sqrt{35}$.
$A=(2,0,-1)\in r$, $B=(0,3,2)\in s$. $\overrightarrow{AB}=(-2,3,3)$.
$\overrightarrow{AB}\cdot(1,-3,-5)=-2-9-15=-26$.
$$d=\frac{|-26|}{\sqrt{35}}=\frac{26}{\sqrt{35}}=\frac{26\sqrt{35}}{35}$$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The minimum distance between two skew lines is achieved along:</li>
<li>a) The direction vector of one of them</li>
<li>b) The common perpendicular direction to both ($\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s$)</li>
<li>c) The bisector of the angle between them</li>
<li>d) Any direction in the plane containing $r$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) The minimum distance is attained along the direction $\vec{n}=\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s$, which is perpendicular to both lines simultaneously.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The formula $d=\dfrac{|\overrightarrow{AB}\cdot(\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s)|}{|\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s|}$ gives the distance between skew lines. If $\overrightarrow{AB}\cdot(\vec{d}_r\times\vec{d}_s)=0$, the lines:</li>
<li>a) Are parallel</li>
<li>b) Intersect (are not skew)</li>
<li>c) Are perpendicular</li>
<li>d) Are coincident</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) If $d=0$, the lines meet (they intersect). We said the direction vectors are not proportional, so they are not parallel; distance zero implies they are intersecting.</p>
</blockquote>
