<h5>5.5.6 Distance between Two Parallel Planes</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Calculate the distance between the parallel planes $\pi_1:\;2x-y+2z=5$ and $\pi_2:\;2x-y+2z=-4$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>For parallel planes of the form $ax+by+cz=d_1$ and $ax+by+cz=d_2$:</p>
<p>$$d(\pi_1,\pi_2) = \frac{|d_1-d_2|}{\sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}}$$</p>
<p>With $a=2$, $b=-1$, $c=2$, $d_1=5$, $d_2=-4$:</p>
<p>$$d=\frac{|5-(-4)|}{\sqrt{4+1+4}}=\frac{9}{\sqrt{9}}=\frac{9}{3}=\boxed{3}$$</p>
<p><strong>Alternative:</strong> Take a point of $\pi_1$ (e.g., $(0,0,5/2)$: $0-0+5=5$ ✓) and calculate its distance to $\pi_2$:
$$d=\frac{|2(0)-0+2(5/2)-(-4)|}{3}=\frac{|0+5+4|}{3}=\frac{9}{3}=3$$ ✓</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Calculate the distance between $\pi_1:\;x+2y-2z=1$ and $\pi_2:\;x+2y-2z=7$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong>
$$d=\frac{|1-7|}{\sqrt{1+4+4}}=\frac{6}{3}=2$$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>When do two planes have distance zero?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> When they are the same plane (coincident). If $\pi_1:\;ax+by+cz=d_1$ and $\pi_2:\;ax+by+cz=d_2$ with $d_1=d_2$, then $d=0$ and $\pi_1=\pi_2$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The planes $\pi_1:\;3x-4y+0z=10$ and $\pi_2:\;3x-4y=k$ are $4$ units apart. Find $k$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong>
$$\frac{|10-k|}{\sqrt{9+16}}=\frac{|10-k|}{5}=4 \Rightarrow |10-k|=20 \Rightarrow k=-10 \text{ or } k=30$$</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find the distance between the planes $\pi_1:\;x+y+z=3$ and $\pi_2:\;2x+2y+2z=10$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> We reduce $\pi_2$: $x+y+z=5$.
$$d=\frac{|3-5|}{\sqrt{3}}=\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}=\frac{2\sqrt{3}}{3}$$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Given the plane $\pi:\;x+2y-2z=4$ and the point $P(1,0,2)$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Find the plane $\sigma$ parallel to $\pi$ passing through $P$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Calculate the distance between $\pi$ and $\sigma$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Find the plane $\tau$ parallel to $\pi$ equidistant from $\pi$ and $\sigma$ (halfway between them).</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $\sigma:\;x+2y-2z=k$. With $P(1,0,2)$: $1+0-4=k=-3$.
$$\sigma:\;x+2y-2z=-3$$</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> $d=\dfrac{|4-(-3)|}{3}=\dfrac{7}{3}$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> $\tau:\;x+2y-2z=m$ equidistant: $\dfrac{|4-m|}{3}=\dfrac{7/3}{2}=\dfrac{7}{6}$, $|4-m|=7/2$: $m=4-7/2=1/2$ or $m=4+7/2=15/2$.
The one between $\pi$ and $\sigma$ (between $d=4$ and $d=-3$): $m=1/2$.
$$\tau:\;x+2y-2z=\frac{1}{2} \quad \text{(or }2x+4y-4z=1\text{)}$$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The distance between the planes $x+y+z=1$ and $x+y+z=-2$ is:</li>
<li>a) $3$</li>
<li>b) $\sqrt{3}$</li>
<li>c) $1$</li>
<li>d) $\dfrac{3}{\sqrt{3}}=\sqrt{3}$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) and d) both give the same result: $d=\dfrac{|1-(-2)|}{\sqrt{3}}=\dfrac{3}{\sqrt{3}}=\sqrt{3}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>To calculate the distance between two parallel planes $\pi_1:\;ax+by+cz+d_1=0$ and $\pi_2:\;ax+by+cz+d_2=0$, one can:</li>
<li>a) Take any point of $\pi_1$ and calculate its distance to $\pi_2$</li>
<li>b) Take the intersection point of the two normal lines</li>
<li>c) Divide $|d_1-d_2|$ by $a+b+c$</li>
<li>d) Measure the length of the vector $\vec{n}$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> a) The distance between parallel planes is constant: the distance from any point of $\pi_1$ to the plane $\pi_2$ always gives the same result, which is the distance between the planes.</p>
</blockquote>
