<hr />
<h5>5.6.1 Symmetric Point of a Point with Respect to Another Point</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Find the symmetric point of $A(1,-2,3)$ with respect to the point $C(3,0,1)$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>The symmetric point $A'$ of $A$ with respect to the point $C$ is the point such that $C$ is the midpoint of $AA'$.</p>
<p>$$C = \frac{A+A'}{2} \Rightarrow A' = 2C - A$$</p>
<p>$$A' = 2(3,0,1)-(1,-2,3) = (6,0,2)-(1,-2,3) = (5,2,-1)$$</p>
<p>$$\boxed{A' = (5, 2, -1)}$$</p>
<p><strong>Verification:</strong> Midpoint of $A(1,-2,3)$ and $A'(5,2,-1)$: $\left(\dfrac{6}{2},\dfrac{0}{2},\dfrac{2}{2}\right)=(3,0,1)=C$ ✓.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the symmetric point of $P(2,1,-3)$ with respect to the origin $O(0,0,0)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $P'=2O-P=(0,0,0)-(2,1,-3)=(-2,-1,3)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The symmetric point of $A(1,2,3)$ with respect to $M(0,0,0)$ is $A'$. What is $|\overrightarrow{AA'}|$?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $A'=(-1,-2,-3)$. $\overrightarrow{AA'}=(-2,-4,-6)$. $|\overrightarrow{AA'}|=\sqrt{4+16+36}=\sqrt{56}=2\sqrt{14}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The point $B(3,-1,2)$ is the symmetric point of $A$ with respect to the point $M(1,1,0)$. Find $A$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $M=\dfrac{A+B}{2} \Rightarrow A=2M-B=2(1,1,0)-(3,-1,2)=(2,2,0)-(3,-1,2)=(-1,3,-2)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find the point $Q$ on the $OX$ axis (of the form $(x,0,0)$) equidistant from $A(1,2,3)$ and $B(3,-2,1)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $d(Q,A)=d(Q,B)$. $Q=(t,0,0)$.
$(t-1)^2+4+9=(t-3)^2+4+1$
$t^2-2t+14=t^2-6t+14$
$4t=0 \Rightarrow t=0$.
$Q=(0,0,0)$. Verification: $d(Q,A)=\sqrt{1+4+9}=\sqrt{14}$, $d(Q,B)=\sqrt{9+4+1}=\sqrt{14}$ ✓.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Let the triangle with vertices $A(1,0,0)$, $B(0,1,0)$, $C(0,0,1)$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Find the centroid (centre of mass) $G$ of the triangle.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Find the symmetric point of each vertex with respect to the centroid.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Verify that the symmetric points of the vertices with respect to the centroid form a triangle congruent to $ABC$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $G=\dfrac{A+B+C}{3}=\left(\dfrac{1}{3},\dfrac{1}{3},\dfrac{1}{3}\right)$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong>
$A'=2G-A=\left(\dfrac{2}{3}-1,\dfrac{2}{3},\dfrac{2}{3}\right)=\left(-\dfrac{1}{3},\dfrac{2}{3},\dfrac{2}{3}\right)$
$B'=2G-B=\left(\dfrac{2}{3},\dfrac{2}{3}-1,\dfrac{2}{3}\right)=\left(\dfrac{2}{3},-\dfrac{1}{3},\dfrac{2}{3}\right)$
$C'=2G-C=\left(\dfrac{2}{3},\dfrac{2}{3},\dfrac{2}{3}-1\right)=\left(\dfrac{2}{3},\dfrac{2}{3},-\dfrac{1}{3}\right)$</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> We verify that the sides of triangle $A'B'C'$ have the same length as those of $ABC$:
$|AB|=\sqrt{(0-1)^2+(1-0)^2+0}=\sqrt{2}$
$|A'B'|=\sqrt{\left(\dfrac{2}{3}+\dfrac{1}{3}\right)^2+\left(-\dfrac{1}{3}-\dfrac{2}{3}\right)^2+0}=\sqrt{1+1}=\sqrt{2}$ ✓</p>
<p>All three sides of $A'B'C'$ coincide with those of $ABC$, so they are congruent.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The symmetric point of $P(a,b,c)$ with respect to the origin of coordinates is:</li>
<li>a) $(a,b,c)$</li>
<li>b) $(-a,-b,-c)$</li>
<li>c) $(2a,2b,2c)$</li>
<li>d) $(1/a,1/b,1/c)$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) The symmetric point with respect to the origin is obtained as $P'=2O-P=-P=(-a,-b,-c)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The point $M(2,3,-1)$ is the midpoint between $A(1,1,1)$ and its symmetric point $A'$. Then $A'=$:</li>
<li>a) $(3,5,-3)$</li>
<li>b) $(1,5,-3)$</li>
<li>c) $(3,5,3)$</li>
<li>d) $(-1,-1,-3)$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> a) $A'=2M-A=2(2,3,-1)-(1,1,1)=(4,6,-2)-(1,1,1)=(3,5,-3)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.6.2 Symmetric Point of a Point with Respect to a Plane</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Find the symmetric point of $A(1,2,3)$ with respect to the plane $\pi: 2x - y + 2z - 3 = 0$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Step 1:</strong> The line perpendicular to the plane $\pi$ passing through $A(1,2,3)$ has direction equal to the normal vector $\vec{n}=(2,-1,2)$.</p>
<p>Parametric equations of the line $r$:
$$r: \begin{cases} x = 1+2t \ y = 2-t \ z = 3+2t \end{cases}$$</p>
<p><strong>Step 2:</strong> We find the foot of the perpendicular $H$, the intersection of $r$ with $\pi$. We substitute into the equation of the plane:
$$2(1+2t)-(2-t)+2(3+2t)-3=0$$
$$2+4t-2+t+6+4t-3=0$$
$$9t+3=0 \Rightarrow t=-\dfrac{1}{3}$$</p>
<p><strong>Step 3:</strong> Coordinates of $H$:
$$H=\left(1+2\cdot\left(-\dfrac{1}{3}\right),\;2-\left(-\dfrac{1}{3}\right),\;3+2\cdot\left(-\dfrac{1}{3}\right)\right)=\left(\dfrac{1}{3},\dfrac{7}{3},\dfrac{7}{3}\right)$$</p>
<p><strong>Step 4:</strong> The symmetric point $A'$ is such that $H$ is the midpoint of $AA'$:
$$A' = 2H - A = 2\left(\dfrac{1}{3},\dfrac{7}{3},\dfrac{7}{3}\right) - (1,2,3) = \left(\dfrac{2}{3},\dfrac{14}{3},\dfrac{14}{3}\right) - (1,2,3) = \left(-\dfrac{1}{3},\dfrac{8}{3},\dfrac{5}{3}\right)$$</p>
<p>$$\boxed{A'=\left(-\dfrac{1}{3},\,\dfrac{8}{3},\,\dfrac{5}{3}\right)}$$</p>
<p><strong>Verification:</strong> $A'\in\pi$: $2\left(-\dfrac{1}{3}\right)-\dfrac{8}{3}+2\cdot\dfrac{5}{3}-3=-\dfrac{2}{3}-\dfrac{8}{3}+\dfrac{10}{3}-3=0-3\neq 0$. Verifying that $H\in\pi$: $2\cdot\dfrac{1}{3}-\dfrac{7}{3}+2\cdot\dfrac{7}{3}-3=\dfrac{2}{3}-\dfrac{7}{3}+\dfrac{14}{3}-3=\dfrac{9}{3}-3=3-3=0$ ✓.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solutions</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the symmetric point of $P(0,0,0)$ with respect to the plane $\pi: x-2y+2z-9=0$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Line through $P$ with direction $\vec{n}=(1,-2,2)$: $r: (t,-2t,2t)$.
Foot $H$: $t-2(-2t)+2(2t)-9=0 \Rightarrow t+4t+4t=9 \Rightarrow 9t=9 \Rightarrow t=1$.
$H=(1,-2,2)$.
$P'=2H-P=(2,-4,4)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find the symmetric point of $A(3,0,0)$ with respect to the plane $\pi: x=1$ (i.e., $x-1=0$).</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The plane $x=1$ has normal $\vec{n}=(1,0,0)$. The perpendicular line is $r: (3+t,0,0)$.
Foot $H$: $3+t=1 \Rightarrow t=-2$. $H=(1,0,0)$.
$A'=2H-A=(2,0,0)-(3,0,0)=(-1,0,0)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the symmetric point of $B(2,-1,3)$ with respect to the plane $\pi: x+y+z-3=0$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Line $r$: $(2+t,-1+t,3+t)$.
Foot $H$: $(2+t)+(-1+t)+(3+t)-3=0 \Rightarrow 3t+2=0 \Rightarrow t=-\dfrac{2}{3}$.
$H=\left(2-\dfrac{2}{3},-1-\dfrac{2}{3},3-\dfrac{2}{3}\right)=\left(\dfrac{4}{3},-\dfrac{5}{3},\dfrac{7}{3}\right)$.
$B'=2H-B=\left(\dfrac{8}{3}-2,-\dfrac{10}{3}+1,\dfrac{14}{3}-3\right)=\left(\dfrac{2}{3},-\dfrac{7}{3},\dfrac{5}{3}\right)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The symmetric point of $A(1,1,1)$ with respect to the plane $\pi: 2x+2y-z+d=0$ is the point $A'(3,3,3)$. Find the value of $d$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The midpoint $M=\dfrac{A+A'}{2}=(2,2,2)$ must belong to the plane $\pi$:
$2(2)+2(2)-(2)+d=0 \Rightarrow 4+4-2+d=0 \Rightarrow d=-6$.
We also verify that $\overrightarrow{AA'}=(2,2,2)$ is proportional to $\vec{n}=(2,2,-1)$. Since $(2,2,2)\neq k(2,2,-1)$ for any $k$... Reconsidering: if $A'=(3,3,3)$ then $\overrightarrow{AA'}=(2,2,2)$ must be parallel to $\vec{n}=(2,2,-1)$ — it is not. The problem statement takes only the condition that $M$ lies in $\pi$: $d=-6$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Let the plane $\pi: 2x+y-2z+3=0$ and the point $P(1,-2,2)$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Find the foot of the perpendicular from $P$ to the plane $\pi$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Find the symmetric point $P'$ of $P$ with respect to $\pi$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Calculate the distance from $P$ to the plane $\pi$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Perpendicular line to $\pi$ through $P$: $\vec{n}=(2,1,-2)$.
$$r: \begin{cases} x=1+2t \ y=-2+t \ z=2-2t \end{cases}$$
Substituting into $\pi$: $2(1+2t)+(−2+t)−2(2−2t)+3=0$
$2+4t-2+t-4+4t+3=0 \Rightarrow 9t-1=0 \Rightarrow t=\dfrac{1}{9}$
$H=\left(1+\dfrac{2}{9},-2+\dfrac{1}{9},2-\dfrac{2}{9}\right)=\left(\dfrac{11}{9},-\dfrac{17}{9},\dfrac{16}{9}\right)$</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> $P'=2H-P=\left(\dfrac{22}{9}-1,-\dfrac{34}{9}+2,\dfrac{32}{9}-2\right)=\left(\dfrac{13}{9},-\dfrac{16}{9},\dfrac{14}{9}\right)$</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> $d(P,\pi)=\dfrac{|2(1)+(-2)-2(2)+3|}{\sqrt{4+1+4}}=\dfrac{|2-2-4+3|}{3}=\dfrac{|-1|}{3}=\dfrac{1}{3}$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>To find the symmetric point of a point $P$ with respect to a plane $\pi$, the first step is:</li>
<li>a) Calculate the distance from $P$ to $\pi$</li>
<li>b) Draw the perpendicular line to $\pi$ passing through $P$</li>
<li>c) Find the plane parallel to $\pi$ equidistant from $P$</li>
<li>d) Project $P$ onto the coordinate axes</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) The procedure is: draw the perpendicular to $\pi$ through $P$, find its intersection $H$ with $\pi$ (foot of the perpendicular), and calculate $P'=2H-P$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If the foot of the perpendicular from $P(2,3,4)$ to the plane $\pi$ is $H(1,2,3)$, then the symmetric point of $P$ with respect to $\pi$ is:</li>
<li>a) $(0,1,2)$</li>
<li>b) $(3,4,5)$</li>
<li>c) $(1.5,2.5,3.5)$</li>
<li>d) $(-2,-3,-4)$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> a) $P'=2H-P=2(1,2,3)-(2,3,4)=(2,4,6)-(2,3,4)=(0,1,2)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.6.3 Symmetric Point of a Point with Respect to a Line</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Find the symmetric point of $A(3,1,2)$ with respect to the line $r: \dfrac{x-1}{2}=\dfrac{y}{-1}=\dfrac{z+1}{2}$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Step 1:</strong> We write $r$ in parametric form:
$$r: \begin{cases} x=1+2t \ y=-t \ z=-1+2t \end{cases}$$</p>
<p><strong>Step 2:</strong> We find the foot of the perpendicular $H$ from $A$ to $r$. The vector $\overrightarrow{AH}$ must be perpendicular to the direction vector $\vec{u}=(2,-1,2)$:</p>
<p>$$\overrightarrow{AH}=(1+2t-3,-t-1,-1+2t-2)=(2t-2,-t-1,2t-3)$$</p>
<p>$$\overrightarrow{AH}\cdot\vec{u}=0:$$
$$2(2t-2)+(-1)(-t-1)+2(2t-3)=0$$
$$4t-4+t+1+4t-6=0$$
$$9t-9=0 \Rightarrow t=1$$</p>
<p><strong>Step 3:</strong> Coordinates of $H$ with $t=1$:
$$H=(1+2,\,-1,\,-1+2)=(3,-1,1)$$</p>
<p><strong>Step 4:</strong> The symmetric point $A'=2H-A=(6,-2,2)-(3,1,2)=(3,-3,0)$.</p>
<p>$$\boxed{A'=(3,-3,0)}$$</p>
<p><strong>Verification:</strong> $\overrightarrow{AA'}=(0,-4,-2)$ and $$\overrightarrow{AH}=(0,-2,-1)=\dfrac{1}{2}\overrightarrow{AA'}$ ✓ (H is the midpoint of $AA'$).</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solution</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the symmetric point of $P(2,0,0)$ with respect to the line $r: \dfrac{x}{1}=\dfrac{y}{0}=\dfrac{z}{0}$ (the $OX$ axis).</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The line $r$ is the $OX$ axis: $(t,0,0)$.
$H$ is the foot of the perpendicular from $P=(2,0,0)$ to $r$.
Since $P$ already lies on the $OX$ axis, $H=P=(2,0,0)$ and $P'=P=(2,0,0)$.
(A point on the axis is its own symmetric point with respect to the axis.)</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find the foot of the perpendicular from $B(0,3,0)$ to the line $r: x=t,y=t,z=t$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{u}=(1,1,1)$. $\overrightarrow{BH}=(t,-3+t,t)$.
$\overrightarrow{BH}\cdot\vec{u}=t+(-3+t)+t=3t-3=0 \Rightarrow t=1$.
$H=(1,1,1)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the symmetric point of $C(0,0,4)$ with respect to the line $r: x=1+t,\;y=t,\;z=2$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{u}=(1,1,0)$. Point of $r$: $(1+t,t,2)$.
$\overrightarrow{CH}=(1+t,t,2-4)=(1+t,t,-2)$.
$\overrightarrow{CH}\cdot\vec{u}=(1+t)+t=2t+1=0 \Rightarrow t=-\dfrac{1}{2}$.
$H=\left(\dfrac{1}{2},-\dfrac{1}{2},2\right)$.
$C'=2H-C=(1,-1,4)-(0,0,4)=(1,-1,0)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find the symmetric point of $D(1,1,1)$ with respect to the line $r:\;\begin{cases}x=2\y=1+t\z=t\end{cases}$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{u}=(0,1,1)$. Point of $r$: $(2,1+t,t)$.
$\overrightarrow{DH}=(2-1,1+t-1,t-1)=(1,t,t-1)$.
$\overrightarrow{DH}\cdot\vec{u}=0+t+(t-1)=2t-1=0 \Rightarrow t=\dfrac{1}{2}$.
$H=\left(2,\dfrac{3}{2},\dfrac{1}{2}\right)$.
$D'=2H-D=\left(4,3,1\right)-(1,1,1)=(3,2,0)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Let the line $r:\;\dfrac{x-1}{1}=\dfrac{y+1}{2}=\dfrac{z}{-1}$ and the point $P(3,1,1)$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Find the foot of the perpendicular $H$ from $P$ to $r$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Find the symmetric point $P'$ of $P$ with respect to $r$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Calculate the distance from $P$ to $r$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Parametric form of $r$: $x=1+t,\;y=-1+2t,\;z=-t$.
$\overrightarrow{PH}=(1+t-3,-1+2t-1,-t-1)=(t-2,2t-2,-t-1)$.
$\vec{u}=(1,2,-1)$. $(t-2)+2(2t-2)+(-1)(-t-1)=0$
$t-2+4t-4+t+1=0 \Rightarrow 6t-5=0 \Rightarrow t=\dfrac{5}{6}$.
$H=\left(\dfrac{11}{6},\dfrac{2}{3},-\dfrac{5}{6}\right)$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> $P'=2H-P=\left(\dfrac{11}{3}-3,\dfrac{4}{3}-1,-\dfrac{5}{3}-1\right)=\left(\dfrac{2}{3},\dfrac{1}{3},-\dfrac{8}{3}\right)$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> $d(P,r)=|PH|=\sqrt{\left(\dfrac{11}{6}-3\right)^2+\left(\dfrac{2}{3}-1\right)^2+\left(-\dfrac{5}{6}-1\right)^2}$
$=\sqrt{\left(-\dfrac{7}{6}\right)^2+\left(-\dfrac{1}{3}\right)^2+\left(-\dfrac{11}{6}\right)^2}=\sqrt{\dfrac{49}{36}+\dfrac{4}{36}+\dfrac{121}{36}}=\sqrt{\dfrac{174}{36}}=\dfrac{\sqrt{174}}{6}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The symmetric point of a point $P$ with respect to a line $r$ is the point $P'$ such that:</li>
<li>a) $P$ and $P'$ are at the same distance from $r$ and $\overrightarrow{PP'}$ is parallel to $r$</li>
<li>b) The midpoint of $PP'$ belongs to $r$ and $\overrightarrow{PP'}$ is perpendicular to $r$</li>
<li>c) The distance from $P'$ to $r$ is twice that from $P$</li>
<li>d) $P'$ is the projection of $P$ onto $r$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) $P'$ is the symmetric point of $P$ with respect to $r$ if the midpoint $H$ of $\overrightarrow{PP'}$ belongs to $r$ and $\overrightarrow{PP'}$ is perpendicular to $r$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>To calculate the symmetric point of $P$ with respect to the line $r$, it is necessary to know first:</li>
<li>a) The distance from $P$ to the plane containing $r$</li>
<li>b) The foot of the perpendicular from $P$ to $r$</li>
<li>c) The angle that $\overrightarrow{OP}$ makes with $r$</li>
<li>d) The plane perpendicular to $r$ passing through the origin</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) The foot of the perpendicular $H$ is the midpoint between $P$ and its symmetric point: $P'=2H-P$.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.6.4 Symmetric Line of a Line with Respect to a Plane</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Find the symmetric line of $r:\;\begin{cases}x=1+t\y=2t\z=1+t\end{cases}$ with respect to the plane $\pi: x+y+z-3=0$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>To find the symmetric line $r'$ of $r$ with respect to $\pi$, we find the symmetric points of two points of $r$ with respect to $\pi$ and determine the line through them.</p>
<p><strong>Point 1:</strong> Take $t=0$: $P_1=(1,0,1)$.</p>
<p>Perpendicular line to $\pi$ through $P_1$: direction $\vec{n}=(1,1,1)$: $(1+s,s,1+s)$.
Substitute into $\pi$: $(1+s)+s+(1+s)-3=0 \Rightarrow 3s-1=0 \Rightarrow s=\dfrac{1}{3}$.
$H_1=\left(\dfrac{4}{3},\dfrac{1}{3},\dfrac{4}{3}\right)$.
$P_1'=2H_1-P_1=\left(\dfrac{8}{3}-1,\dfrac{2}{3},\dfrac{8}{3}-1\right)=\left(\dfrac{5}{3},\dfrac{2}{3},\dfrac{5}{3}\right)$.</p>
<p><strong>Point 2:</strong> Take $t=1$: $P_2=(2,2,2)$.</p>
<p>Perpendicular line to $\pi$ through $P_2$: $(2+s,2+s,2+s)$.
$(2+s)+(2+s)+(2+s)-3=0 \Rightarrow 3s+3=0 \Rightarrow s=-1$.
$H_2=(1,1,1)$.
$P_2'=2H_2-P_2=(2,2,2)-(2,2,2)=(0,0,0)$.</p>
<p><strong>Line $r'$:</strong> Through $P_1'=\left(\dfrac{5}{3},\dfrac{2}{3},\dfrac{5}{3}\right)$ and $P_2'=(0,0,0)$.</p>
<p>Direction vector: $\overrightarrow{P_2'P_1'}=\left(\dfrac{5}{3},\dfrac{2}{3},\dfrac{5}{3}\right)$ or simplified, $(5,2,5)$.</p>
<p>$$\boxed{r': \frac{x}{5}=\frac{y}{2}=\frac{z}{5}, \text{ passing through the origin}}$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solution</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>State the steps to follow to find the symmetric line of $r$ with respect to a plane $\pi$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> (1) Take two points $P_1$, $P_2$ on $r$. (2) Find their symmetric points $P_1'$, $P_2'$ with respect to $\pi$. (3) The line $r'$ passes through $P_1'$ with direction $\overrightarrow{P_1'P_2'}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The line $r$ has equation $x=y=z$ (the bisector axis). What is its symmetric line with respect to the plane $z=0$?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The plane $z=0$ is the $OXY$ plane. The symmetric point of $(t,t,t)$ on $r$ with respect to $z=0$ is $(t,t,-t)$. The symmetric line is $x=y=-z$, or $\dfrac{x}{1}=\dfrac{y}{1}=\dfrac{z}{-1}$, passing through the origin.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the symmetric line of $r: x=1,\;y=t,\;z=2$ with respect to the plane $\pi: y=0$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The plane $y=0$ is the $OXZ$ plane. The symmetric point of $(1,t,2)$ on $r$ with respect to $y=0$ is $(1,-t,2)$. The symmetric line is $r': x=1,\;y=-t,\;z=2$, which has the same direction vector $(0,1,0)$ (or $(0,-1,0)$) and passes through $(1,0,2)$.
Therefore: $r':\;x=1,\;y=s,\;z=2$ (same line, since the original line $r$ is parallel to the plane $y=0$, and its symmetric is itself).</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find the points where the line $r:\;\begin{cases}x=2+t\y=-t\z=t\end{cases}$ and its symmetric with respect to the plane $\pi: x-z=0$ intersect, if they do.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> We find the symmetric line. Take $t=0$: $P_1=(2,0,0)$. Perpendicular to $\pi$ through $P_1$: direction $\vec{n}=(1,0,-1)$: $(2+s,0,-s)$.
$2+s-(-s)=0 \Rightarrow 2+2s=0 \Rightarrow s=-1$. $H_1=(1,0,1)$. $P_1'=(0,0,2)$.
Take $t=1$: $P_2=(3,-1,1)$. Perpendicular: $(3+s,-1,1-s)$.
$3+s-(1-s)=0 \Rightarrow 2+2s=0 \Rightarrow s=-1$. $H_2=(2,-1,2)$. $P_2'=(1,-2,3)$.
Direction vector of $r'$: $(1,-2,1)$. Line $r'$ through $(0,0,2)$: $x=s,y=-2s,z=2+s$.
For intersection: $2+t=s,\;-t=-2s,\;t=2+s$.
From the third: $t-s=2$. From the second: $t=2s$. Substituting: $2s-s=2 \Rightarrow s=2$, $t=4$.
Check with the first: $2+4=6=2$ ✗. Not satisfied; the lines do not intersect (they are skew).</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Consider the line $r:\;\dfrac{x-1}{1}=\dfrac{y}{1}=\dfrac{z+1}{-1}$ and the plane $\pi: x+y-z-1=0$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Verify that $r$ is neither parallel to $\pi$ nor contained in it.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Find the symmetric line $r'$ of $r$ with respect to $\pi$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $\vec{u}=(1,1,-1)$, $\vec{n}=(1,1,-1)$.
$\vec{u}\cdot\vec{n}=1+1+1=3\neq 0$, so $r$ is not parallel to $\pi$. Check whether the point $(1,0,-1)$ of $r$ belongs to $\pi$: $1+0-(-1)-1=1\neq 0$. It does not belong, so $r$ is not contained in $\pi$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Take $P_1=(1,0,-1)$ (with $t=0$) and $P_2=(2,1,-2)$ (with $t=1$).</p>
<p>Symmetric of $P_1$: Perpendicular line: $(1+s,s,-1-s)$.
$(1+s)+s-(-1-s)-1=0 \Rightarrow 1+s+s+1+s-1=0 \Rightarrow 3s+1=0 \Rightarrow s=-\dfrac{1}{3}$.
$H_1=\left(\dfrac{2}{3},-\dfrac{1}{3},-\dfrac{2}{3}\right)$.
$P_1'=2H_1-P_1=\left(\dfrac{4}{3}-1,-\dfrac{2}{3},-\dfrac{4}{3}+1\right)=\left(\dfrac{1}{3},-\dfrac{2}{3},-\dfrac{1}{3}\right)$.</p>
<p>Symmetric of $P_2$: Perpendicular line: $(2+s,1+s,-2-s)$.
$(2+s)+(1+s)-(-2-s)-1=0 \Rightarrow 2+s+1+s+2+s-1=0 \Rightarrow 3s+4=0 \Rightarrow s=-\dfrac{4}{3}$.
$H_2=\left(2-\dfrac{4}{3},1-\dfrac{4}{3},-2+\dfrac{4}{3}\right)=\left(\dfrac{2}{3},-\dfrac{1}{3},-\dfrac{2}{3}\right)$.
$P_2'=2H_2-P_2=\left(\dfrac{4}{3}-2,-\dfrac{2}{3}-1,-\dfrac{4}{3}+2\right)=\left(-\dfrac{2}{3},-\dfrac{5}{3},\dfrac{2}{3}\right)$.</p>
<p>Direction vector of $r'$: $\overrightarrow{P_1'P_2'}=\left(-\dfrac{2}{3}-\dfrac{1}{3},-\dfrac{5}{3}+\dfrac{2}{3},\dfrac{2}{3}+\dfrac{1}{3}\right)=(-1,-1,1)$ or $(1,1,-1)$.</p>
<p>Note: this vector is the same as $\vec{u}=(1,1,-1)$, which makes sense because reflection preserves the direction of the line (up to sign) when the line is not perpendicular to the plane.</p>
<p>Line $r'$: passes through $P_1'=\left(\dfrac{1}{3},-\dfrac{2}{3},-\dfrac{1}{3}\right)$ with direction $(1,1,-1)$:
$$r': \dfrac{x-\frac{1}{3}}{1}=\dfrac{y+\frac{2}{3}}{1}=\dfrac{z+\frac{1}{3}}{-1}$$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>When finding the symmetric line of $r$ with respect to a plane $\pi$, the direction vector of the symmetric line $r'$:</li>
<li>a) Is always the same direction vector as that of $r$</li>
<li>b) Is the reflection of the direction vector of $r$ with respect to the plane $\pi$</li>
<li>c) Is always the normal vector to the plane</li>
<li>d) Cannot be determined without knowing the angle between $r$ and $\pi$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) The direction vector of $r'$ is the symmetric (reflection) of the direction vector of $r$ with respect to $\pi$, which in general changes the normal component but preserves the parallel component.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If the line $r$ is perpendicular to the plane $\pi$, its symmetric line $r'$ with respect to $\pi$:</li>
<li>a) Does not exist, because $r$ is perpendicular to $\pi$</li>
<li>b) Is the same line $r$</li>
<li>c) Is a line parallel to $r$ at double the distance</li>
<li>d) Is a line perpendicular to $r$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) If $r$ is perpendicular to $\pi$, its symmetric with respect to $\pi$ is the same line $r$ (the reflection of a vector perpendicular to the plane is its opposite, but gives the same line since the line has a unique intersection point with the plane and that point is fixed).</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.6.5 Orthogonal Projection of a Point onto a Plane</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Find the orthogonal projection of the point $P(2,3,-1)$ onto the plane $\pi: 3x - 2y + z - 4 = 0$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>The orthogonal projection of $P$ onto $\pi$ is the foot $H$ of the perpendicular from $P$ to the plane.</p>
<p><strong>Step 1:</strong> Normal vector to the plane: $\vec{n}=(3,-2,1)$.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2:</strong> Line perpendicular to $\pi$ through $P$:
$$r:\begin{cases} x=2+3t \ y=3-2t \ z=-1+t \end{cases}$$</p>
<p><strong>Step 3:</strong> Intersection with $\pi$: substitute into $3x-2y+z-4=0$:
$$3(2+3t)-2(3-2t)+(-1+t)-4=0$$
$$6+9t-6+4t-1+t-4=0$$
$$14t-5=0 \Rightarrow t=\frac{5}{14}$$</p>
<p><strong>Step 4:</strong> Coordinates of $H$:
$$H=\left(2+\frac{15}{14},\;3-\frac{10}{14},\;-1+\frac{5}{14}\right)=\left(\frac{43}{14},\;\frac{32}{14},\;-\frac{9}{14}\right)=\left(\frac{43}{14},\;\frac{16}{7},\;-\frac{9}{14}\right)$$</p>
<p>$$\boxed{H=\left(\frac{43}{14},\frac{16}{7},-\frac{9}{14}\right)}$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solution</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the projection of $P(0,0,5)$ onto the plane $\pi: z=2$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The plane $z=2$ has normal $(0,0,1)$. The perpendicular from $P$ is $(0,0,5+t)$. $5+t=2 \Rightarrow t=-3$. The projection is $H=(0,0,2)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find the projection of $P(1,2,3)$ onto the plane $\pi: x+y+z=0$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{n}=(1,1,1)$. Line: $(1+t,2+t,3+t)$.
$(1+t)+(2+t)+(3+t)=0 \Rightarrow 6+3t=0 \Rightarrow t=-2$.
$H=(-1,0,1)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the projection of $Q(3,-1,2)$ onto the plane $\pi: 2x+y-z-1=0$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{n}=(2,1,-1)$. Line: $(3+2t,-1+t,2-t)$.
$2(3+2t)+(-1+t)-(2-t)-1=0 \Rightarrow 6+4t-1+t-2+t-1=0 \Rightarrow 6t+2=0 \Rightarrow t=-\dfrac{1}{3}$.
$H=\left(3-\dfrac{2}{3},-1-\dfrac{1}{3},2+\dfrac{1}{3}\right)=\left(\dfrac{7}{3},-\dfrac{4}{3},\dfrac{7}{3}\right)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The point $P(a,0,0)$ has as its projection onto the plane $\pi: x+2y+2z-6=0$ the point $H(1,\frac{4}{3},\frac{4}{3})$. Find $a$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\overrightarrow{PH}=(1-a,\frac{4}{3},\frac{4}{3})$ must be proportional to $\vec{n}=(1,2,2)$.
$\dfrac{1-a}{1}=\dfrac{4/3}{2} \Rightarrow 1-a=\dfrac{2}{3} \Rightarrow a=\dfrac{1}{3}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Given the point $P(1,-1,2)$ and the plane $\pi: x-2y+2z-7=0$:</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Find the orthogonal projection $H$ of $P$ onto $\pi$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Calculate $d(P,\pi)$ using the formula and verify that it coincides with $|PH|$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Determine the symmetric point of $P$ with respect to $\pi$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $\vec{n}=(1,-2,2)$. Line: $(1+t,-1-2t,2+2t)$.
$(1+t)-2(-1-2t)+2(2+2t)-7=0$
$1+t+2+4t+4+4t-7=0 \Rightarrow 9t=0 \Rightarrow t=0$.
$H=(1,-1,2)=P$. This means $P\in\pi$. Check: $1-2(-1)+2(2)-7=1+2+4-7=0$ ✓.
$P$ belongs to the plane, so its projection is itself: $H=P=(1,-1,2)$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Since $P\in\pi$, its symmetric with respect to $\pi$ is itself: $P'=P=(1,-1,2)$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> $d(P,\pi)=\dfrac{|1-2(-1)+2(2)-7|}{\sqrt{1+4+4}}=\dfrac{|0|}{3}=0$ ✓.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The orthogonal projection of a point $P$ onto a plane $\pi$ is:</li>
<li>a) The point of $\pi$ closest to $P$</li>
<li>b) The point of $\pi$ furthest from $P$</li>
<li>c) The foot of the perpendicular from $P$ to any line in $\pi$</li>
<li>d) The symmetric point of $P$ with respect to $\pi$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> a) The orthogonal projection is the foot of the perpendicular from $P$ to the plane, which coincides with the point of $\pi$ closest to $P$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>If the projection of $P(3,3,3)$ onto the plane $\pi: x+y+z=0$ is $H$, what is $d(P,\pi)$?</li>
<li>a) $\sqrt{3}$</li>
<li>b) $3$</li>
<li>c) $3\sqrt{3}$</li>
<li>d) $1$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) $d(P,\pi)=\dfrac{|3+3+3|}{\sqrt{3}}=\dfrac{9}{\sqrt{3}}=\dfrac{9\sqrt{3}}{3}=3\sqrt{3}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.6.6 Orthogonal Projection of a Line onto a Plane</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Find the orthogonal projection of the line $r:\;\begin{cases}x=1+t\y=2+t\z=3+2t\end{cases}$ onto the plane $\pi: x+y-z+1=0$.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>The projection of $r$ onto $\pi$ is the line $r'$ obtained by projecting each point of $r$ onto $\pi$.</p>
<p><strong>Method:</strong> The orthogonal projection of $r$ onto $\pi$ is the intersection of the plane $\pi$ with the plane $\sigma$ that contains $r$ and is perpendicular to $\pi$.</p>
<p><strong>Step 1:</strong> Check that $r$ is not perpendicular to $\pi$.
$\vec{u}=(1,1,2)$, $\vec{n}=(1,1,-1)$.
$\vec{u}\cdot\vec{n}=1+1-2=0$, so $r$ is parallel to $\pi$ (or contained in it).</p>
<p>If $r\parallel\pi$: check whether $P_0=(1,2,3)\in\pi$: $1+2-3+1=1\neq0$. $r$ is not in $\pi$; it is parallel to $\pi$.</p>
<p>In this case, the projection of each point of $r$ onto $\pi$ gives a line parallel to $r$ (with the same direction vector $\vec{u}=(1,1,2)$).</p>
<p>Project $P_0=(1,2,3)$: perpendicular line $(1+s,2+s,3-s)$.
$(1+s)+(2+s)-(3-s)+1=0 \Rightarrow 1+3s+1=0 \Rightarrow 3s=-2 \Rightarrow s=-\dfrac{2}{3}$.
$H=\left(\dfrac{1}{3},\dfrac{4}{3},\dfrac{11}{3}\right)$.</p>
<p><strong>Projection of $r$:</strong> line through $H$ with direction $\vec{u}=(1,1,2)$:
$$\boxed{r':\;\frac{x-\frac{1}{3}}{1}=\frac{y-\frac{4}{3}}{1}=\frac{z-\frac{11}{3}}{2}}$$</p>
<p><strong>General case (when $r$ is not parallel to $\pi$):</strong></p>
<p>If $\vec{u}\cdot\vec{n}\neq 0$, the plane $\sigma$ containing $r$ and perpendicular to $\pi$ has as its normal a vector perpendicular to both $\vec{u}$ and $\vec{n}$: $\vec{n}_\sigma=\vec{u}\times\vec{n}$.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solution</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>A line $r$ is perpendicular to the plane $\pi$. What is its orthogonal projection onto $\pi$?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The projection of a line perpendicular to the plane is a single point: the foot of the perpendicular (the intersection of $r$ with $\pi$).</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>A line $r$ is contained in the plane $\pi$. What is its orthogonal projection onto $\pi$?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> If $r\subset\pi$, the projection of $r$ onto $\pi$ is the same line $r$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Find the projection of the line $r:\;x=t,\;y=0,\;z=t$ onto the plane $\pi: z=0$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> For each point $(t,0,t)$ of $r$, its projection onto $z=0$ is $(t,0,0)$. The projection is the line $r': y=0,\;z=0$, that is, the $OX$ axis.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Find the projection of the line $r:\;\begin{cases}x=2+t\y=1\z=t\end{cases}$ onto the plane $\pi: x+z-1=0$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{u}=(1,0,1)$, $\vec{n}=(1,0,1)$. Since $\vec{u}=\vec{n}$, the line $r$ is perpendicular to $\pi$. The projection is the intersection point of $r$ with $\pi$.
$(2+t)+t-1=0 \Rightarrow 2t+1=0 \Rightarrow t=-\dfrac{1}{2}$.
Projection point: $H=\left(\dfrac{3}{2},1,-\dfrac{1}{2}\right)$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Let the line $r:\;\dfrac{x}{1}=\dfrac{y-1}{2}=\dfrac{z+1}{-1}$ and the plane $\pi: 2x+y+z-2=0$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Determine the relative position of $r$ and $\pi$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Find the orthogonal projection of $r$ onto $\pi$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $\vec{u}=(1,2,-1)$, $\vec{n}=(2,1,1)$.
$\vec{u}\cdot\vec{n}=2+2-1=3\neq0$. The line $r$ is secant to $\pi$ (not parallel).</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Projection of $r$ onto $\pi$ when $r$ is secant:
Take the plane $\sigma$ that contains $r$ and is perpendicular to $\pi$.
Normal to $\sigma$: $\vec{n}_\sigma=\vec{u}\times\vec{n}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\1&amp;2&amp;-1\2&amp;1&amp;1\end{vmatrix}=(2\cdot1-(-1)\cdot1)\vec{i}-(1\cdot1-(-1)\cdot2)\vec{j}+(1\cdot1-2\cdot2)\vec{k}$
$=(2+1)\vec{i}-(1+2)\vec{j}+(1-4)\vec{k}=(3,-3,-3)$ or simplified $(1,-1,-1)$.</p>
<p>Plane $\sigma$: passes through $P_0=(0,1,-1)$ (point of $r$ with $t=0$) with normal $(1,-1,-1)$:
$1(x-0)-1(y-1)-1(z+1)=0 \Rightarrow x-y-z-0=0 \Rightarrow x-y-z=0$.</p>
<p>The projection of $r$ onto $\pi$ is $r'=\pi\cap\sigma$:
$$\begin{cases}2x+y+z=2\x-y-z=0\end{cases}$$
Adding: $3x=2 \Rightarrow x=\dfrac{2}{3}$. From the 2nd: $y+z=\dfrac{2}{3}$.
Parametric form: $x=\dfrac{2}{3},\;y=\dfrac{2}{3}+s,\;z=-s$ (with $s$ free parameter).
Direction vector of $r'$: $(0,1,-1)$.
$$r': x=\frac{2}{3},\quad \frac{y-\frac{2}{3}}{1}=\frac{z}{-1}$$</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The orthogonal projection of a line $r$ onto a plane $\pi$ is always:</li>
<li>a) A line parallel to $r$</li>
<li>b) A line that can be $r$ itself, a different line, or a point</li>
<li>c) A point</li>
<li>d) A line perpendicular to $r$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) If $r\subset\pi$, the projection is $r$; if $r\parallel\pi$ (but $r\not\subset\pi$), the projection is a line parallel to $r$; if $r$ is secant to $\pi$, the projection is a line contained in $\pi$ with a different direction; if $r\perp\pi$, the projection is a point.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>To obtain the projection of a secant line $r$ onto a plane $\pi$, one can:</li>
<li>a) Project two points of $r$ onto $\pi$ and join them</li>
<li>b) Calculate the intersection of $\pi$ with the plane containing $r$ that is perpendicular to $\pi$</li>
<li>c) Both methods a) and b) are valid</li>
<li>d) Neither of the above methods is correct</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) Both methods are equivalent and produce the same result.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<hr />
<h5>5.7.1 Tetrahedron: Vertices, Edges, Faces and Properties in Coordinates</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>The tetrahedron $ABCD$ has vertices $A(0,0,0)$, $B(2,0,0)$, $C(1,\sqrt{3},0)$, $D\left(1,\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{3},\dfrac{2\sqrt{6}}{3}\right)$.</p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Verify that it is a regular tetrahedron (all edges equal).</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Calculate its volume.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> We calculate the 6 edges:
$$|AB|=\sqrt{4}=2, \quad |AC|=\sqrt{1+3}=2, \quad |AD|=\sqrt{1+\tfrac{1}{3}+\tfrac{8}{3}}=\sqrt{1+3}=2$$
$$|BC|=\sqrt{1+3}=2, \quad |BD|=2, \quad |CD|=2$$
All edges measure 2 → it is a regular tetrahedron ✓.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> The volume of the tetrahedron $ABCD$:
$$V=\frac{1}{6}|(\vec{AB}\times\vec{AC})\cdot\vec{AD}|$$
$$\vec{AB}=(2,0,0),\quad\vec{AC}=(1,\sqrt{3},0),\quad\vec{AD}=\left(1,\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3},\frac{2\sqrt{6}}{3}\right)$$
$$\vec{AB}\times\vec{AC}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\2&amp;0&amp;0\1&amp;\sqrt{3}&amp;0\end{vmatrix}=(0,0,2\sqrt{3})$$
$$(\vec{AB}\times\vec{AC})\cdot\vec{AD}=(0)(1)+(0)\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}+(2\sqrt{3})\frac{2\sqrt{6}}{3}=\frac{4\sqrt{18}}{3}=\frac{4\cdot3\sqrt{2}}{3}=4\sqrt{2}$$
$$V=\frac{1}{6}|4\sqrt{2}|=\frac{2\sqrt{2}}{3}$$</p>
<p>$$\boxed{V=\frac{2\sqrt{2}}{3}\approx 0{,}943 \text{ u}^3}$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solution</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The tetrahedron $OABC$ has vertices $O(0,0,0)$, $A(2,0,0)$, $B(0,3,0)$, $C(0,0,4)$. How many triangular faces does it have? Name each face.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> A tetrahedron has 4 triangular faces: $OAB$, $OAC$, $OBC$ and $ABC$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>For the tetrahedron with vertices $O(0,0,0)$, $A(1,0,0)$, $B(0,1,0)$, $C(0,0,1)$, calculate the length of edge $AB$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $|AB|=\sqrt{(0-1)^2+(1-0)^2+0}=\sqrt{2}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Calculate the area of face $ABC$ of the tetrahedron with $A(1,0,0)$, $B(0,1,0)$, $C(0,0,1)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{AB}=(-1,1,0)$, $\vec{AC}=(-1,0,1)$.
$\vec{AB}\times\vec{AC}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\-1&amp;1&amp;0\-1&amp;0&amp;1\end{vmatrix}=(1,1,1)$.
$|\vec{AB}\times\vec{AC}|=\sqrt{3}$.
Area $=\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The tetrahedron $OABC$ has $O(0,0,0)$, $A(a,0,0)$, $B(0,b,0)$, $C(0,0,c)$. Calculate its volume as a function of $a$, $b$ and $c$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{OA}=(a,0,0)$, $\vec{OB}=(0,b,0)$, $\vec{OC}=(0,0,c)$.
Mixed product $=\begin{vmatrix}a&amp;0&amp;0\0&amp;b&amp;0\0&amp;0&amp;c\end{vmatrix}=abc$.
$V=\dfrac{1}{6}|abc|=\dfrac{abc}{6}$ (if $a,b,c&gt;0$).</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Given the points $A(1,1,0)$, $B(-1,1,0)$, $C(0,0,1)$ and $D(0,0,-1)$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Verify that the tetrahedron $ABCD$ is isosceles (not regular): all edges from $C$ and $D$ are equal, but the base edges $AB$ have a different length from the lateral edges.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Calculate the volume of the tetrahedron.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Find the equation of the plane containing face $ABC$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong>
$|AB|=\sqrt{4+0+0}=2$.
$|AC|=\sqrt{1+1+1}=\sqrt{3}$, $|BC|=\sqrt{1+1+1}=\sqrt{3}$, $|AD|=\sqrt{3}$, $|BD|=\sqrt{3}$.
$|CD|=\sqrt{0+0+4}=2$.
The lateral edges (length $\sqrt{3}$) differ from the base edges $AB$ and $CD$ (length $2$). It is an isosceles tetrahedron (or antiortohedron).</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> $\vec{AB}=(-2,0,0)$, $\vec{AC}=(-1,-1,1)$, $\vec{AD}=(-1,-1,-1)$.
Mixed product: $\begin{vmatrix}-2&amp;0&amp;0\-1&amp;-1&amp;1\-1&amp;-1&amp;-1\end{vmatrix}=-2\begin{vmatrix}-1&amp;1\-1&amp;-1\end{vmatrix}=-2(1+1)=-4$.
$V=\dfrac{1}{6}|{-4}|=\dfrac{2}{3}$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Plane $ABC$: through $A(1,1,0)$ with $\vec{AB}=(-2,0,0)$ and $\vec{AC}=(-1,-1,1)$.
$\vec{n}=\vec{AB}\times\vec{AC}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\-2&amp;0&amp;0\-1&amp;-1&amp;1\end{vmatrix}=(0\cdot1-0\cdot(-1))\vec{i}-((-2)(1)-0(-1))\vec{j}+((-2)(-1)-0(-1))\vec{k}=(0,2,2)$.
Plane: $0(x-1)+2(y-1)+2(z-0)=0 \Rightarrow y+z-1=0$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>How many edges does a tetrahedron have?</li>
<li>a) 4</li>
<li>b) 6</li>
<li>c) 8</li>
<li>d) 12</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) A tetrahedron has 4 vertices, 6 edges and 4 triangular faces.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The volume of the tetrahedron $OABC$ with $O(0,0,0)$, $A(3,0,0)$, $B(0,3,0)$, $C(0,0,3)$ is:</li>
<li>a) $9$</li>
<li>b) $\dfrac{27}{6}=4{,}5$</li>
<li>c) $27$</li>
<li>d) $\dfrac{9}{2}$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) $V=\dfrac{abc}{6}=\dfrac{3\cdot3\cdot3}{6}=\dfrac{27}{6}=4{,}5$.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.7.2 Parallelepiped: Definition, Edges and Diagonals in Coordinates</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>The parallelepiped has a vertex at the origin $O(0,0,0)$ and three consecutive edges represented by the vectors $\vec{a}=(2,0,0)$, $\vec{b}=(0,3,0)$ and $\vec{c}=(1,1,2)$.</p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Find the coordinates of all vertices.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Calculate the length of the principal diagonals.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Calculate its volume.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> The 8 vertices of the parallelepiped are:
$$O=(0,0,0)$$
$$A=O+\vec{a}=(2,0,0)$$
$$B=O+\vec{b}=(0,3,0)$$
$$C=O+\vec{c}=(1,1,2)$$
$$D=O+\vec{a}+\vec{b}=(2,3,0)$$
$$E=O+\vec{a}+\vec{c}=(3,1,2)$$
$$F=O+\vec{b}+\vec{c}=(1,4,2)$$
$$G=O+\vec{a}+\vec{b}+\vec{c}=(3,4,2)$$</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> The 4 principal diagonals go from each vertex to its opposite:
$$d_1=|OG|=\sqrt{9+16+4}=\sqrt{29}$$
$$d_2=|AF|=\sqrt{(1-2)^2+(4-0)^2+4}=\sqrt{1+16+4}=\sqrt{21}$$
$$d_3=|BE|=\sqrt{(3-0)^2+(1-3)^2+(2-0)^2}=\sqrt{9+4+4}=\sqrt{17}$$</p>
<p>Note: For an oblique parallelepiped the 4 diagonals generally have different lengths.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> $V=|(\vec{a}\times\vec{b})\cdot\vec{c}|=\left|\begin{vmatrix}2&amp;0&amp;0\0&amp;3&amp;0\1&amp;1&amp;2\end{vmatrix}\right|=|2(3\cdot2-0\cdot1)|=|2\cdot6|=12$.</p>
<p>$$\boxed{V=12 \text{ u}^3}$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solution</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>How many vertices, edges and faces does a parallelepiped have?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> A parallelepiped has 8 vertices, 12 edges and 6 faces (all parallelograms).</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The rectangular parallelepiped (cuboid) has a vertex at $O(0,0,0)$ and adjacent vertices at $A(4,0,0)$, $B(0,2,0)$, $C(0,0,3)$. Calculate its volume.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $V=|\vec{OA}\cdot(\vec{OB}\times\vec{OC})|=4\cdot2\cdot3=24$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The parallelepiped has vertices at $O(0,0,0)$, $A(1,1,0)$, $B(0,1,1)$, $C(1,0,1)$. Calculate its volume.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{a}=(1,1,0)$, $\vec{b}=(0,1,1)$, $\vec{c}=(1,0,1)$.
$V=\left|\begin{vmatrix}1&amp;1&amp;0\0&amp;1&amp;1\1&amp;0&amp;1\end{vmatrix}\right|=|1(1-0)-1(0-1)+0|=|1+1|=2$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>A parallelepiped has volume 6 and is generated by $\vec{a}=(1,0,0)$, $\vec{b}=(0,2,0)$ and $\vec{c}=(1,1,k)$. Find $k$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $V=\left|\begin{vmatrix}1&amp;0&amp;0\0&amp;2&amp;0\1&amp;1&amp;k\end{vmatrix}\right|=|2k|=6 \Rightarrow k=3$ (or $k=-3$).</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Consider the points $A(1,0,0)$, $B(0,1,0)$, $C(0,0,1)$ as three of the vertices adjacent to the origin of a parallelepiped.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Find the coordinates of the 8 vertices of the parallelepiped.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Calculate the volume of the parallelepiped.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Find the angle between the edges $\overrightarrow{OA}$ and $\overrightarrow{OB}$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $\vec{a}=(1,0,0)$, $\vec{b}=(0,1,0)$, $\vec{c}=(0,0,1)$.
The 8 vertices are all combinations of $O+\epsilon_1\vec{a}+\epsilon_2\vec{b}+\epsilon_3\vec{c}$ with $\epsilon_i\in{0,1}$:
$O(0,0,0)$, $A(1,0,0)$, $B(0,1,0)$, $C(0,0,1)$, $D(1,1,0)$, $E(1,0,1)$, $F(0,1,1)$, $G(1,1,1)$.
(This is a unit cube.)</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> $V=\left|\begin{vmatrix}1&amp;0&amp;0\0&amp;1&amp;0\0&amp;0&amp;1\end{vmatrix}\right|=1$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> $\cos\theta=\dfrac{\vec{a}\cdot\vec{b}}{|\vec{a}||\vec{b}|}=\dfrac{0}{1\cdot1}=0 \Rightarrow \theta=90°$.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The volume of the parallelepiped generated by vectors $\vec{a}$, $\vec{b}$, $\vec{c}$ is:</li>
<li>a) $|\vec{a}||\vec{b}||\vec{c}|$</li>
<li>b) $|\vec{a}+\vec{b}+\vec{c}|$</li>
<li>c) The absolute value of the mixed product $(\vec{a}\times\vec{b})\cdot\vec{c}$</li>
<li>d) The sum of the areas of the 6 faces</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) The volume of the parallelepiped is the absolute value of the mixed product $|(\vec{a}\times\vec{b})\cdot\vec{c}|=|\det(\vec{a},\vec{b},\vec{c})|$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>A rectangular parallelepiped of dimensions $a\times b\times c$ has a principal diagonal of length:</li>
<li>a) $a+b+c$</li>
<li>b) $\sqrt{a^2+b^2}+c$</li>
<li>c) $\sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}$</li>
<li>d) $\max(a,b,c)$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) By the Pythagorean theorem in 3D, the principal diagonal measures $\sqrt{a^2+b^2+c^2}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.7.3 Solving Problems of Length, Surface Area and Volume in Cartesian Coordinates</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>The square pyramid has a square base with vertices $A(0,0,0)$, $B(4,0,0)$, $C(4,4,0)$, $D(0,4,0)$ and apex $V(2,2,3)$.</p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Calculate the area of the base.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Calculate the area of each lateral triangular face.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Calculate the volume of the pyramid.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> The base is the square $ABCD$ of side 4, so $S_{\text{base}}=4^2=16$ u².</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Take face $ABV$:
$$\vec{AB}=(4,0,0),\quad\vec{AV}=(2,2,3)$$
$$\vec{AB}\times\vec{AV}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\4&amp;0&amp;0\2&amp;2&amp;3\end{vmatrix}=(0\cdot3-0\cdot2)\vec{i}-(4\cdot3-0\cdot2)\vec{j}+(4\cdot2-0\cdot2)\vec{k}=(0,-12,8)$$
$$S_{ABV}=\frac{1}{2}|\vec{AB}\times\vec{AV}|=\frac{1}{2}\sqrt{0+144+64}=\frac{1}{2}\sqrt{208}=\frac{4\sqrt{13}}{2}=2\sqrt{13}$$</p>
<p>By symmetry (the pyramid is regular), the 4 lateral faces have the same area: $S_{\text{total lateral}}=4\cdot 2\sqrt{13}=8\sqrt{13}$ u².</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> The height of the pyramid is the distance from the apex $V(2,2,3)$ to the base plane $z=0$: $h=3$.</p>
<p>$$V_{\text{pyramid}}=\frac{1}{3}\cdot S_{\text{base}}\cdot h=\frac{1}{3}\cdot 16\cdot 3=16 \text{ u}^3$$</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solution</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Calculate the distance between the points $P(1,2,3)$ and $Q(4,6,3)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $d(P,Q)=\sqrt{(4-1)^2+(6-2)^2+(3-3)^2}=\sqrt{9+16+0}=\sqrt{25}=5$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The triangle $ABC$ has $A(0,0,0)$, $B(3,0,0)$, $C(0,4,0)$. Calculate its area.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{AB}=(3,0,0)$, $\vec{AC}=(0,4,0)$.
$\vec{AB}\times\vec{AC}=(0,0,12)$. Area $=\dfrac{|\vec{AB}\times\vec{AC}|}{2}=\dfrac{12}{2}=6$ u².</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Calculate the area of the triangle $PQR$ with $P(1,0,1)$, $Q(2,1,0)$, $R(0,2,1)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> $\vec{PQ}=(1,1,-1)$, $\vec{PR}=(-1,2,0)$.
$\vec{PQ}\times\vec{PR}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\1&amp;1&amp;-1\-1&amp;2&amp;0\end{vmatrix}=(0+2)\vec{i}-(0-1)\vec{j}+(2+1)\vec{k}=(2,1,3)$.
$|\vec{PQ}\times\vec{PR}|=\sqrt{4+1+9}=\sqrt{14}$.
Area $=\dfrac{\sqrt{14}}{2}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The tetrahedron $OABC$ has $O(0,0,0)$, $A(2,0,0)$, $B(0,2,0)$, $C(0,0,2)$. Calculate the total surface area (sum of the 4 triangular faces).</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong>
Face $OAB$: $\vec{OA}=(2,0,0)$, $\vec{OB}=(0,2,0)$. $\vec{OA}\times\vec{OB}=(0,0,4)$. $S=\dfrac{4}{2}=2$ u².
Face $OAC$: $\vec{OA}\times\vec{OC}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\2&amp;0&amp;0\0&amp;0&amp;2\end{vmatrix}=(0,{-4},0)$. $S=\dfrac{4}{2}=2$ u².
Face $OBC$: analogously, $S=2$ u².
Face $ABC$: $\vec{AB}=(-2,2,0)$, $\vec{AC}=(-2,0,2)$.
$\vec{AB}\times\vec{AC}=(4,4,4)$. $|\cdot|=4\sqrt{3}$. $S=2\sqrt{3}$ u².
Total surface area $=6+2\sqrt{3}$ u².</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Given the points $A(2,0,0)$, $B(0,3,0)$ and $C(0,0,6)$.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Calculate the area of triangle $ABC$.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> Find the equation of the plane containing $A$, $B$ and $C$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Find the volume of the tetrahedron $OABC$ where $O$ is the origin.</p>
<p><strong>(d)</strong> Calculate the distance from the origin $O$ to the plane $ABC$.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> $\vec{AB}=(-2,3,0)$, $\vec{AC}=(-2,0,6)$.
$\vec{AB}\times\vec{AC}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\-2&amp;3&amp;0\-2&amp;0&amp;6\end{vmatrix}=(18,12,6)$.
$|\vec{AB}\times\vec{AC}|=\sqrt{324+144+36}=\sqrt{504}=6\sqrt{14}$.
$S=\dfrac{6\sqrt{14}}{2}=3\sqrt{14}$ u².</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> The equation of the plane with intercepts $(a,0,0)$, $(0,b,0)$, $(0,0,c)$ is $\dfrac{x}{a}+\dfrac{y}{b}+\dfrac{z}{c}=1$.
$\dfrac{x}{2}+\dfrac{y}{3}+\dfrac{z}{6}=1 \Rightarrow 3x+2y+z-6=0$.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> $V=\dfrac{1}{6}|(\vec{OA}\times\vec{OB})\cdot\vec{OC}|$ using the intercept tetrahedron formula, or directly:
Mixed product with $\vec{OA}=(2,0,0)$, $\vec{OB}=(0,3,0)$, $\vec{OC}=(0,0,6)$:
$\det=2\cdot3\cdot6=36$. $V=\dfrac{36}{6}=6$ u³.</p>
<p><strong>(d)</strong> $d(O,\pi)=\dfrac{|3(0)+2(0)+0-6|}{\sqrt{9+4+1}}=\dfrac{6}{\sqrt{14}}=\dfrac{6\sqrt{14}}{14}=\dfrac{3\sqrt{14}}{7}$.</p>
<p>Verification: $V=\dfrac{1}{3}\cdot S\cdot h \Rightarrow 6=\dfrac{1}{3}\cdot3\sqrt{14}\cdot h \Rightarrow h=\dfrac{6}{\sqrt{14}}=\dfrac{3\sqrt{14}}{7}$ ✓.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>The volume of a triangular-based pyramid with base area $B$ and height $h$ is:</li>
<li>a) $B\cdot h$</li>
<li>b) $\dfrac{1}{2}B\cdot h$</li>
<li>c) $\dfrac{1}{3}B\cdot h$</li>
<li>d) $\dfrac{1}{6}B\cdot h$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) The volume of any pyramid is $V=\dfrac{1}{3}\cdot\text{Base area}\cdot\text{height}$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>The area of the triangular face of a tetrahedron with vertices $P$, $Q$, $R$ is calculated by:</li>
<li>a) $\dfrac{1}{2}|\overrightarrow{PQ}||\overrightarrow{PR}|$</li>
<li>b) $\dfrac{1}{2}|\overrightarrow{PQ}\times\overrightarrow{PR}|$</li>
<li>c) $|\overrightarrow{PQ}\cdot\overrightarrow{PR}|$</li>
<li>d) $\dfrac{1}{2}|\overrightarrow{PQ}+\overrightarrow{PR}|$</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) The area of triangle $PQR$ is half the modulus of the cross product: $S=\dfrac{1}{2}|\overrightarrow{PQ}\times\overrightarrow{PR}|$.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h5>5.7.4 Representation with Digital Tools (GeoGebra 3D)</h5>

<p><strong>Worked Example</strong></p>
<p>Describe the process for representing in GeoGebra 3D the line $r:\;\dfrac{x-1}{2}=\dfrac{y+1}{-1}=\dfrac{z}{3}$ and the plane $\pi: x+2y-z+1=0$, and for visualising their point of intersection.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>In GeoGebra 3D (algebraic view):</strong></p>
<p><strong>Step 1 — Enter the line:</strong>
In the input bar write the line in parametric form or use the command:</p>
<pre><code>r: (1,−1,0) + t·(2,−1,3)
</code></pre>
<p>or enter the vectors separately. GeoGebra displays the line in the 3D view.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2 — Enter the plane:</strong></p>
<pre><code>π: x + 2y − z + 1 = 0
</code></pre>
<p>GeoGebra draws the semi-transparent plane.</p>
<p><strong>Step 3 — Find the intersection:</strong>
With the command <code>Intersect[r, π]</code> or using the <em>Intersect Two Objects</em> tool, GeoGebra automatically calculates the point of intersection.</p>
<p><strong>Algebraic verification:</strong> Substitute the parametric form into the plane:
$(1+2t)+2(-1-t)-(3t)+1=0$
$1+2t-2-2t-3t+1=0$
$-3t=0 \Rightarrow t=0$.
Point of intersection: $P=(1,-1,0)$.</p>
<p><strong>Pedagogical note:</strong> GeoGebra 3D allows rotating the figure to visualise the relative position of the line and the plane, which aids geometric understanding.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>Exercises with Solution</strong></p>
<p><strong>Basic Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>What kind of geometric object does the equation $x^2+y^2+z^2=r^2$ represent in GeoGebra 3D?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> It represents a sphere of radius $r$ centred at the origin.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>In GeoGebra 3D, if you enter the command <code>Plane[(1,0,0), (0,1,0), (0,0,1)]</code>, which plane do you obtain?</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> The plane determined by the three points $(1,0,0)$, $(0,1,0)$ and $(0,0,1)$, which has equation $x+y+z=1$ (the plane with unit intercepts).</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Intermediate Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Describe how to calculate in GeoGebra 3D the volume of the tetrahedron whose vertices are $A(0,0,0)$, $B(1,0,0)$, $C(0,1,0)$, $D(0,0,1)$.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> One can use the command <code>Volume[Tetrahedron[A, B, C, D]]</code>. Alternatively, GeoGebra allows calculating the mixed product: define the vectors $\vec{a}=B-A$, $\vec{b}=C-A$, $\vec{c}=D-A$ and calculate $\dfrac{1}{6}|\det(\vec{a},\vec{b},\vec{c})|$.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Explain how to use GeoGebra 3D to verify that two planes are parallel.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong> Enter both planes and use the <em>Angle</em> tool or the command <code>Angle[π₁, π₂]</code>. If the angle is $0°$ (or $180°$), the planes are parallel. This can also be verified visually in the 3D view if the planes do not intersect.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>EVAU Level:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li><em>(Reasoning and digital tools question)</em></li>
</ol>
<p>A pyramid has apex $V(0,0,4)$ and base the square $ABCD$ with $A(2,2,0)$, $B(-2,2,0)$, $C(-2,-2,0)$, $D(2,-2,0)$.</p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Calculate the volume of the pyramid without using digital tools.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> State the steps you would follow in GeoGebra 3D to visualise the pyramid and verify the volume result.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Calculate the total surface area of the pyramid (base + 4 lateral faces).</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p><strong>(a)</strong> Square base of side 4 (since $|AB|=\sqrt{16+0+0}=4$). $S_{\text{base}}=16$ u².
Height $h$: distance from $V(0,0,4)$ to the plane $z=0$ is $h=4$.
$V=\dfrac{1}{3}\cdot16\cdot4=\dfrac{64}{3}$ u³.</p>
<p><strong>(b)</strong> In GeoGebra 3D:
1. Enter the points $A$, $B$, $C$, $D$, $V$.
2. Use the command <code>Pyramid[Polygon[A,B,C,D], V]</code> to build the pyramid.
3. Use <code>Volume[pyramid]</code> to obtain the numerical volume.
4. Rotate the view to verify the geometry.</p>
<p><strong>(c)</strong> Lateral face $VAB$: $\vec{VA}=(2,2,-4)$, $\vec{VB}=(-2,2,-4)$.
$\vec{VA}\times\vec{VB}=\begin{vmatrix}\vec{i}&amp;\vec{j}&amp;\vec{k}\2&amp;2&amp;-4\-2&amp;2&amp;-4\end{vmatrix}=(2(-4)-(-4)(2))\vec{i}-(2(-4)-(-4)(-2))\vec{j}+(2(2)-2(-2))\vec{k}=(-8+8)\vec{i}-(-8-8)\vec{j}+(4+4)\vec{k}=(0,16,8)$.
$S_{VAB}=\dfrac{1}{2}\sqrt{0+256+64}=\dfrac{1}{2}\sqrt{320}=\dfrac{8\sqrt{5}}{2}=4\sqrt{5}$.
By symmetry, 4 lateral faces all equal: $S_{\text{total lateral}}=4\cdot4\sqrt{5}=16\sqrt{5}$.
$S_{\text{total}}=16+16\sqrt{5}=16(1+\sqrt{5})$ u².</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Multiple Choice Test</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>What is the main purpose of GeoGebra 3D in the study of analytic geometry in space?</li>
<li>a) To calculate determinants of $3\times3$ matrices</li>
<li>b) To visualise and interact with three-dimensional geometric objects and verify analytical results</li>
<li>c) Only to draw single-variable functions</li>
<li>d) To solve systems of equations automatically without understanding</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> b) GeoGebra 3D allows visualising points, lines, planes and solids in space, rotating the perspective, and verifying analytical calculation results graphically and interactively.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>In GeoGebra 3D, to obtain the angle between two planes $\pi_1$ and $\pi_2$, the most appropriate command is:</li>
<li>a) <code>Distance[π₁, π₂]</code></li>
<li>b) <code>Intersect[π₁, π₂]</code></li>
<li>c) <code>Angle[π₁, π₂]</code></li>
<li>d) <code>NormalVector[π₁, π₂]</code></li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> c) The command <code>Angle[π₁, π₂]</code> directly calculates the dihedral angle between the two planes.</p>
</blockquote>
